football team|Brazil Olympic]] | nationalcaps2 = 17\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1995\u20132006 | nationalteam3 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] | nationalcaps3 = 91\n| nationalgoals3  = 0\n| pcupdate = 03:21, 7 September 2015 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|BRA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 France]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 Japan\u2013South Korea]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1995 Uruguay]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1999 Paraguay]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup|1997 Saudi Arabia]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[1999 FIFA Confederations Cup|1999 Mexico]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|2005 Germany]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[1996 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1996 United States]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta]]|[[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA U-20 World Cup|FIFA U\u201320 World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1993 FIFA World Youth Championship|1993 Australia]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[South American Youth Football Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1992 South American U-20 Championship|1992 Colombia]]|}}\n}}\n'''N\u00e9lson de Jesus Silva'''{{#tag:ref|Full name has been incorrectly given as ''Nelson Jesus Dida''<ref name=\"espngotta\"/> or ''Nelson Jesus da Silva''.<ref name=\"surgiu\"/> While with Milan, he was regularly called '''Nelson Dida''' by Italian media.<ref name=\"acmilanHOF\"/><ref name=\"maidire\"/><ref name=\"celtic2\"/><ref name=\"ultimouomo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimouomo.com/una-storia-incompleta/|title=Nelson Dida: Una storia incompleta|first=Davide|last=Coppo|work=ultimouomo.com|language=Italian|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} (born 7 October 1973), better known simply as '''Dida''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8d\u0292id\u0250|br}}), is a Brazilian former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. After starting his senior club career in Brazil in the early 1990s with [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria|Vit\u00f3ria]], Dida became a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]-saving specialist with [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]] and [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]]. He is perhaps best remembered for his successful and often tumultuous ten-year stint with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] from 2000 to 2010, where he established himself as one of the world's best goalkeepers due to his shot-stopping ability and command of the area;<ref name=\"penpics\">{{cite news|last=May|first=John|title=AC Milan Pen Pics|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6658701.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 January 2013|date=22 May 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\">{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2004/12/09/fenomeno-dida-un-felino-tra-pali-il.html|title=Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=Andrea Sorrentino|date=9 December 2004|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> he won multiple trophies and individual awards with the club, but became equally known for his propensity for errors as well as his excellent gameplay,<ref name=\"maidire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maidirecalcio.com/2015/10/23/nelson-dida.html|title=Nelson Dida: tra papere, miracoli e petardi, storia del Dottor Jekyll & Mister Hyde del Milan|first=Stelle|last=Cadenti|work=MaiDireCalcio.com|language=Italian|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\"/><ref name=\"trionfi\">{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2010/giugno/08/Ciao_Dida_Trionfi_papere_poche_ga_10_100608044.shtml|title=Ciao Dida: Trionfi, papere e poche parole|first=Andrea|last=Schianchi|work=archiviostorico.gazzetta.it|language=Italian|date=8 June 2010|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"sudamerica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calciosudamericano.it/lettere-dal-sud-america-dida-e-le-montagne-russe/|title=Lettere dal Sud America \u2013 Dida e le montagne russe|first=Michele|last=Bresciani|work=CalcioSudamericano.it|language=Italian|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> while he gained media attention in 2005 for being hit by a lit [[Flare (pyrotechnic)|flare]] during a match against [[Derby della Madonnina|crosstown rivals]] [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://talksport.com/football/champions-league-quarter-final-flashback-2005-milan-derby-abandoned-150414143148|title=Champions League quarter-final flashback: 2005 Milan derby abandoned|first=Damian|last=Mannion|work=TalkSport.com|date=14 April 2015|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/espn-fc-united-blog/68/post/1840794/top-tenner-world-footballs-most-violent-derbies|title=Top Tenner: World football's most violent derbies|first=Nick|last=Miller|work=ESPN FC|date=29 August 2013|accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nDida won one [[Serie A]] title (''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]'') and twice the [[UEFA Champions League]] with Milan, with the first of those victories coming after he saved three penalties in the 2003 [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|final]] against [[Juventus F.C.\u2013A.C. Milan rivalry|Serie A rivals]] [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archivio.panorama.it/archivio/Milan-campione-La-Juve-s-inchina-ai-rigori|title=Milan campione. La Juve s'inchina ai rigori|work=archivio.panorama.it|first=Matteo|last=Durante|language=Italian|date=2003|accessdate=22 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504054715/http://archivio.panorama.it/archivio/Milan-campione-La-Juve-s-inchina-ai-rigori|archive-date=4 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/blogs/74/post/2021634/the-22-champions-league-winners|title=The 22 Champions League winners|work=ESPN FC|first1=Miguel|last1=Delaney|first2=Andrew|last2=Rush|date=7 September 2014|accessdate=10 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031737/http://www.espnfc.us/blogs/74/post/2021634/the-22-champions-league-winners|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref> One of four ''Rossoneri'' goalies with over 300 total career appearances,<ref name=\"milan300\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/121917|title=300 TIMES DIDA|work=ACMilan.com|date=17 May 2010|accessdate=7 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419091446/http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/121917|archivedate=19 April 2016 }}</ref> Dida was inducted into Milan's Hall of Fame in 2014, and has joined other former club players for various off-pitch events and exhibition matches following his 2010 departure. After a two-year absence from playing, he returned to Brazil in 2012, suiting up for three teams\u2014[[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]], [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] and [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\u2014in as many seasons.\n\nAt international level, Dida earned 91 [[Cap (sport)|cap]]s in 11 years with the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]], winning the [[FIFA World Cup]] and an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] medal, and is the most successful player in the history of the [[FIFA Confederations Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/videos/y=2013/m=6/video=dida-amazing-record-2111068.html|title=Dida's amazing record|work=FIFA.com|date=17 June 2013|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He notably broke a color barrier during the [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] by being the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o's'' first [[Afro-Brazilian]] starting goalkeeper since [[Moacir Barbosa Nascimento|Moacyr Barbosa]] half a century earlier.<ref name=\"futebol\">Bellos, Alex. ''Futebol: The Brazilian Way of Life'' (p. 56). Bloomsbury USA (2002), {{ISBN|1620402440}}.</ref> He retired from international play after Brazil were eliminated in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup#Quarter-finals|2006 FIFA World Cup quarter-finals]].\n\nConsidered to be one of the best goalkeepers of his generation,<ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\"/> Dida is the first goalkeeper in history to become the goalkeeper of the year in 2005 by [[FIFPro]] and the first Brazilian goalkeeper to be nominated for the [[FIFA Ballon d'Or]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifpro.org/en/award-history/fifpro-world-xi-2004-2005|title=FIFPro World XI 2004/2005|work=fifpro.org|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"oglobo\"/> is the first two-time winner of the [[FIFA Club World Cup]], a seven-time nominee of the [[IFFHS]] [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper|World's Best Goalkeeper]] award, and is one of only nine players to win both the Champions League and the [[Copa Libertadores]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/eclcopalib.html|title=European Champions League and Copa Libertadores Champions|first=Luca|last=Gandini|work=rsssf.com|date=9 June 2016|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> He was named the best [[Latin Americans|Latin American]] keeper,<ref name=\"21st\"/> and the sixth-best keeper overall, of the 21st century by [[IFFHS]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?d85ff8b00388f05e91a01bccdc4205fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb883910 |title= Gianluigi Buffon ahead of Iker Casillas by a hair |publisher=iffhs.de |date=7 February 2012 |accessdate=7 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208195541/http://www.iffhs.de/?d85ff8b00388f05e91a01bccdc4205fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb883910 |archivedate=8 February 2012}}</ref> and is widely rated among the all-time greats in the position for Brazil alongside [[Marcos Roberto Silveira Reis|Marcos]], [[Rog\u00e9rio Ceni]], [[Cl\u00e1udio Taffarel]] and [[Gylmar dos Santos Neves|Gilmar]].{{efn|See<ref name=\"21st\"/><ref name=\"sempretrio\">{{cite web|url=http://esportefinal.lance.com.br/dida-rogerio-e-marcos-um-trio-para-sempre/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920044208/http://esportefinal.lance.com.br/dida-rogerio-e-marcos-um-trio-para-sempre/|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 September 2016|title=Dida, Rog\u00e9rio e Marcos: um trio para sempre|trans-title=Dida, Rog\u00e9rio e Marcos: forever a trio|first=Jose|last=Antonio Lima|work=esportefinal.lance.com.br|language=Portuguese|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mg.superesportes.com.br/app/noticias/futebol/futebol-nacional/2016/02/16/noticia_futebol_nacional,329697/sem-renovacao-de-contrato-goleiro-dida-segue-no-futebol-e-estuda-para-ser-treinador.shtml|title=Sem renova\u00e7\u00e3o de contrato, goleiro Dida segue no futebol e estuda para ser treinador|work=mg.superesportes.com.br|author=Ag\u00eancia Estado|language=Portuguese|date=2 February 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"rincon\">S\u00edmon, Lu\u00eds Augusto. ''Os 11 maiores goleiros do futebol brasileiro''. Editora Contexto (2010). {{ISBN|978-85-7244-546-7}}.</ref><ref name=\"90min\">{{cite web|url=http://www.90min.com/it/posts/2782669-i-10-migliori-portieri-brasiliani-della-storia|title=I 10 migliori portieri brasiliani della storia|work=90min.com|first=Davide|last=Martini|language=Italian|date=9 December 2015|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Brazil's 10 Best Goalkeepers\">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1478781-ranking-brazils-10-best-goalkeepers-of-all-time |title=Ranking Brazil's 10 Best Goalkeepers of All Time |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |first=Christopher|last=Atkins|date=10 January 2013 |accessdate=21 January 2019 }}</ref>}} He has been credited with helping end the prejudice against black goalkeepers in Brazilian club football due to his success in Europe,<ref name=\"goleirosnegros\">{{cite web|url=http://esporte.uol.com.br/futebol/ultimas-noticias/2012/11/17/presenca-de-goleiros-negros-aumenta-mas-eles-ainda-sao-minoria.htm|title= Presen\u00e7a de goleiros negros no Brasil salta de 12,5% para 31% em oito anos|author=Rodrigo Dur\u00e3o Coelho|work=esporte.uol.com.br|language=Portuguese|date=17 November 2012|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blackwomenofbrazil.co/2013/02/02/after-decades-of-racist-stereotypes-questioning-their-ability-black-goalies-in-brazilian-soccer-jumps-18-5-in-eight-years/|title=After decades of racist stereotypes questioning their ability, black goalies in Brazilian soccer jumps 18.5% in eight years|work=blackwomenofbrazil.co|date=2 February 2013|accessdate=21 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006004346/https://blackwomenofbrazil.co/2013/02/02/after-decades-of-racist-stereotypes-questioning-their-ability-black-goalies-in-brazilian-soccer-jumps-18-5-in-eight-years/|archivedate=6 October 2017}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Contains English translation of previous source.|group=\"nb\"}} and upon joining Internacional in 2014, became the first Afro-Brazilian keeper to play for the club in 43 years.<ref name=\"43anos\">{{cite web|url=http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/esportes/inter/noticia/2014/01/com-dida-inter-volta-a-ter-um-goleiro-negro-depois-de-43-anos-4386406.html=|title=Com Dida, Inter volta a ter um goleiro negro depois de 43 anos|first=Leandro|last=Behs|work=Zero Hora|language=Portuguese|date=10 January 2014|accessdate=7 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419055434/http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/esportes/inter/noticia/2014/01/com-dida-inter-volta-a-ter-um-goleiro-negro-depois-de-43-anos-4386406.html|archivedate=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nN\u00e9lson de Jesus Silva was born on 7 October 1973 in the city of [[Irar\u00e1]] in the northeastern Brazilian state of [[Bahia]], and is one of eight children along with five sisters and two brothers.<ref name=\"surgiu\">{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rs/futebol/times/gremio/noticia/2013/10/da-propaganda-festas-na-bahia-os-40-anos-de-dida-o-goleiro-calado.html|title=Da propaganda \u00e0s festas na Bahia: 40 anos de Dida, o 'goleiro calado'|first=Hector|last=Werlang|work=[[Globo Esporte]]|language=Portuguese|date=7 October 2013|accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref> He was raised in [[Lagoa da Canoa]] in the smaller neighboring state of [[Alagoas]], to where his family had moved when he was three months old.<ref name=\"diariopenadense\">{{cite web|url=http://diariopenedense.com.br/2015/11/10/goleiro-dida-recebe-titulo-de-cidadao-honorario-de-alagoas/|title=Goleiro Dida recebe t\u00edtulo de cidad\u00e3o honor\u00e1rio de Alagoas|work=Diario Penedense|language=Portuguese|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=17 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325145709/http://diariopenedense.com.br/2015/11/10/goleiro-dida-recebe-titulo-de-cidadao-honorario-de-alagoas/|archivedate=25 March 2016}}</ref> His first sport of choice was [[volleyball]], which he played with his brothers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esportes.terra.com.br/volei/dida-prestigia-selecao-de-volei-e-diz-que-prioriza-propostas-da-europa,c79882bd0faaa310VgnCLD200000bbcceb0aRCRD.html|title=Dida prestigia Sele\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00f4lei e diz que prioriza propostas da Europa|work=[[ESPN]]|first=Celso|last=Paiva|language=Portuguese|date=25 September 2010|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> until he discovered football by way of [[futsal]] and pickup games.<ref name=\"fifaprep\"/> His preferred position was that of [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]],<ref name=\"placar1001\">\"Ele nem pisca\" (He never blinks), ''[[Placar]]'' #1201 (October 2001), p. 21.</ref> despite its longtime unpopularity in Brazilian football and the country's history of discrimination against [[Black people|black]] players in the position.<ref name=\"goleirosnegros\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/sports/2014/03/18/brazil-soccer-culture-neglects-goalkeeping-at-national-squad-peril/|title=Brazil's Soccer Culture Neglects Goalkeeping, At National Squad's Peril|work=[[Fox Sports]] Latino|date=18 March 2014|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nA supporter of [[Rio de Janeiro]]-based club [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]],<ref name=\"fifamag\">{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fanfest/magazine/magazine01-06p.4en_3112.pdf | title = 25 Questions 25 Answers: Dida | publisher=FIFA Magazine |date=January 2006}}</ref> Dida helped form an amateur squad called ''Flamenguinho'' (\"little Flamengo\") at age thirteen,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://esportes.yahoo.com/noticias/criado-em-alagoas-exgoleiro-dida-relembra-epoca-na-roca-e-flamenguinho-orgulho-de-ter-comecado-ai-090022181.html|title=Criado em Alagoas, ex-goleiro Dida relembra \u00e9poca na ro\u00e7a e Flamenguinho: \"Orgulho de ter come\u00e7ado a\u00ed\"|first=Josue|last=Seixas|first2=Rafael|last2=Brito|work=Yahoo! Esportes|language=Portuguese|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=31 October 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101061136/https://esportes.yahoo.com/noticias/criado-em-alagoas-exgoleiro-dida-relembra-epoca-na-roca-e-flamenguinho-orgulho-de-ter-comecado-ai-090022181.html|archivedate=1 November 2019}}</ref> which marked his first experience in organized team play.<ref name=\"fifaprep\"/> He took his future playing name from revered Flamengo striker [[Edvaldo Alves de Santa Rosa|Dida]],<ref name=\"zerohora\">{{cite web|url=http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/esportes/gremio/noticia/2013/09/festeiro-e-personagem-de-livro-na-bahia-o-dida-que-ninguem-conhece-4268378.html|title=Festeiro e personagem de livro na Bahia: o Dida que ningu\u00e9m conhece |author=Jones Lopes da Silva|work=[[Zero Hora]]|language=Portuguese|date=14 September 2013|accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref> while his footballing idols were goalkeepers [[Rinat Dasayev]]<ref name=\"fifaprep\">{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/178/822/0/index.html| title=Dida: It's all about preparation | work=[[FIFA]]|date=19 October 2012|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> and future ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' teammate [[Cl\u00e1udio Taffarel]], who had enjoyed successful runs in [[Serie A|Italy]] and [[S\u00fcper Lig|Turkey]] and whom Dida considered a pioneer in the growing acceptance of Brazilian keepers into European clubs.<ref name=\"oglobo\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n=== Vit\u00f3ria, Cruzeiro, and Corinthians===\n{{quote box|width=300px|\"<nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Bahia]]n football] teams featured many homegrown talents. [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria|Vit\u00f3ria]] ... had players like Dida, [[Vampeta]], Giuliano, [[Rodrigo (footballer, born 1973)|Rodrigo]], [[Paulo Isidoro]], [[Alexandro Alves do Nascimento|Alex Alves]]. A nineteen-year-old goalkeeper in Dida, defending a club like Vit\u00f3ria, though he was black. And whenever a black goalkeeper played [in Brazil], he was under suspicion.\"|source=\u2014Former Vit\u00f3ria teammate Jo\u00e3o Marcelo, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/ba/noticia/2014/10/dificil-para-o-negro-amuleto-baiano-ex-zagueiro-quer-chance-como-tecnico.html |title=\"Dif\u00edcil para o negro\": amuleto baiano, ex-zagueiro quer chance como t\u00e9cnico|trans-title='Hard for a black': Bahian talisman and ex-defender wants a chance as coach|first=Eric Luis|last=Carvalho|work=globoesporte.globo.com|language=Portuguese|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>}}\nIn 1990, at age 17, Dida made his club football debut with now-defunct Alagoan team Cruzeiro de [[Arapiraca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minutoarapiraca.cadaminuto.com.br/noticia/14917/2014/12/28/alvaro-melo-e-goleiro-dida-discutem-importancia-do-esporte-em-lagoa-da-canoa|title=\u00c1lvaro Melo e goleiro Dida discutem import\u00e2ncia do esporte em Lagoa da Canoa|work=Minuto Arapiraca|language=Portuguese|date=28 December 2014|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> Two years later, he joined the youth academy of hometown team and 1992 [[Campeonato Baiano]] winners [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria|Vit\u00f3ria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mensolympic/destination/cities/city=50071/index.html|title=Olympic Football Tournament Rio 2016 - Salvador|work=FIFA.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"placar194\">''Placar'' #1090 (January 1994), p. 5.</ref> In 1993, after starting in Brazil's [[1993 FIFA World Youth Championship|FIFA World Youth Championship]] victory, Dida made 24 starts in goal for Vit\u00f3ria's senior squad as they finished runner-up to [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]] in the [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]], and he became the youngest recipient, at 20, of Brazilian football magazine ''[[Placar]]'s'' annual ''Bola de Prata'' award as the S\u00e9rie A's best goalkeeper.<ref name=\"placar194\"/>\n\nDida was then acquired by [[Minas Gerais]]-based club [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]] in 1994, and in a span of five seasons, he won four [[Campeonato Mineiro|state titles]], the [[1996 Copa do Brasil]] and the [[1997 Copa Libertadores]], and two more ''Bola de Prata'' goalkeeping awards. However, in January 1999 he publicly stated his desire to test his skills in Europe and catch the attention of the [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian national team]] coaching staff in the process,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.atribuna.com.br/futebolinternacional/goleiro-dida-quer-voltar-a-jogar-futebol/|title=Goleiro Dida quer voltar a jogar futebol|first=Bruno|last=Rios|language=Portuguese|work=atribuna.com.br|date=12 May 2012|accessdate=20 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819062316/http://blogs.atribuna.com.br/futebolinternacional/goleiro-dida-quer-voltar-a-jogar-futebol/|archive-date=19 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and therefore took the club to court in order to cancel the remainder of his contract so he could sign with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], the only European team that had extended him an offer.<ref name=\"placar899\">''\"Na\u00e7\u00e3o Defendida\"'' [\"Nation Defended\"], ''Placar'' #1154 (August 1999), p. 50-52.</ref> The ensuing legal battle between the player and Cruzeiro lasted for five months,<ref name=\"placar899\"/> and a [[FIFA]] ruling allowed Dida to be loaned to Swiss club [[FC Lugano]] in the meantime so he could keep in shape, though he never played a game.<ref name=\"acmonline\">{{cite web | url = http://www.acmilan-online.com/cgi-bin/newspro/viewnews.cgi?newsid1129134005,21236, | title = Player Profile: Dida |first=Aaron|last=Marcus| work=Goal.com (reposted on acmilan-online.com) |date=September 2005|accessdate=26 July 2006}}</ref> His move to Milan was finalized in May 1999 with a transfer fee of 2.7 billion [[Italian lira|Italian lire]] ([[Brazilian real|R$]]5.2 million) paid to Cruzeiro, which brought the dispute to a close.<ref name=\"placar899\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dgabc.com.br/Noticia/271486/cruzeiro-fecha-com-milan-e-dida-pode-parar-no-corinthians|title=Cruzeiro fecha com Milan e Dida pode parar no Corinthians|trans-title=Cruzeiro closes with Milan and Dida free to go to Corinthians|work=Di\u00e1rio de Grande ABC|language=Portuguese|date=26 May 1999|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nDida was the third goalkeeper on Milan coach [[Alberto Zaccheroni]]'s depth chart behind [[Christian Abbiati]] and aging veteran [[Sebastiano Rossi]] for the [[1999\u20132000 Serie A]] season, and he returned to Brazil as he was loaned to [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]-based club [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]] to receive regular playing time. During this stint, his reputation as a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] stopper came into national renown<ref name=\"edmundo\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=1999/m=12/news=who-will-down-history-71904.html|title=Who will go down in history?|work=FIFA.com|date=31 December 1999|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> after he saved two separate spot kicks\u2014both taken by [[Ra\u00ed]]\u2014in Corinthians' 3\u20132 victory over intrastate rival [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC]] in the [[1999 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|1999 Campeonato Brasileiro]] semi-final.<ref name=\"lance\">{{cite web | url = http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991201/isp01080.html | title = Chilavert sets record on goalkeepers' day | work = The Indian Express | date = 12 December 1999 | accessdate = 22 March 2008 |url-status=dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080229035717/http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991201/isp01080.html | archivedate = 29 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goltv.tv/index.php/es/social/blogs/8122-gringo-fiel|title=Gringo Fiel|work=goltv.tv|first=Adam|last=Hurrey|date=9 April 2015|accessdate=27 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031053706/https://www.goltv.tv/index.php/es/social/blogs/8122-gringo-fiel|archive-date=31 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Dida received his first nomination for the [[IFFHS]] [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper|World's Best Goalkeeper]] award that season, finishing eighth in the voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-gkoy99.html|title=IFFHS' World's Best Goalkeeper of the Year 1999|work=rsssf.com|date=28 January 2001|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> In 2000, he kept three clean sheets in four matches while allowing only two goals as Corinthians lifted the inaugural [[2000 FIFA Club World Championship|FIFA Club World Cup]]. After the 15 January final against [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]] ended goalless after extra time, he blocked a [[Gilberto da Silva Melo|Gilberto]] penalty in the shootout that Corinthians won 4\u20133 after Vasco striker [[Edmundo (footballer)|Edmundo]]'s shot went wide right.<ref name=\"edmundo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jan/15/newsstory.sport9|title=Corinthians rejoice as Edmundo misses|work=The Guardian|date=15 January 2000|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> Corinthians midfielder [[Ricardinho]] revealed to the media afterward that the team was actively seeking to take the match to penalties during the extra period, knowing Dida would save \"at least one in five\";<ref name=\"FdSP-1\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/esporte/fk1601200007.htm|title=\"N\u00e3o quero mais p\u00eanaltis\", afirma Dida|trans-title=\"I don't like penalties,\" Dida says|first=Rodrigo|last=Bueno|work=Folha de S.Paulo|language=Portuguese|date=16 January 2000|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> indeed, [[BBC News]] castigated the \"poor final\" as both teams \"never look[ing] like scoring in two hours of open play\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1999/12/99/world_club_championship/604434.stm|title=Corinthians crowned world champions |first=Alan|last=Green|work=BBC News|date=15 January 2000|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> while Dida himself criticized penalty shootouts in that they \"cause[d] suffering to the players and the fans\".<ref name=\"FdSP-1\"/>\n\n=== Milan===\n\n====1999\u20132002: Beginnings with Milan and return to Corinthians====\nMilan recalled Dida and named him their [[2000\u201301 UEFA Champions League|2000\u201301 Champions League]] starter with first-choice [[Christian Abbiati]] on international duty with [[Italy national football team|Italy]] at the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Summer Olympics]]. His ''Rossoneri'' debut was a 4\u20131 group stage victory over [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] on 13 September 2000, but six days later, against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] at a rain-soaked [[Elland Road]], he accidentally dropped a [[Lee Bowyer]] strike into his own goal, causing Milan to lose the match 1\u20130.<ref name=\"uefa305\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/21/sports/21iht-soccer.2.t_10.html | title =Manchester United Manages a Draw in Kiev |work=NYTimes.com |first=Rob |last=Hughes|date = 21 September 2000 | accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> His explanation was that he attempted to absorb the force of the shot and then catch hold of it, but the ball dropped into a puddle and bounced into the net.<ref name=\"espngotta\">{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=364072&root=europe&cc=5901|last=Gotta|first=Roberto|title=Dodgy keeper?|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=7 April 2006|accessdate=26 July 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111002727/http://www.espnfc.com/story/364072|archivedate=11 January 2015}}</ref> He started the remaining group stage games and kept his first clean sheet for Milan in a 2\u20130 win over [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on 26 September,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/championsleague/2000/20000926/reports/barcelona_acmilan_full.html|title=Milan pick off Barcelona in classy win|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=26 September 2000|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> but was then replaced by Abbiati for the [[2000\u201301 UEFA Champions League second group stage|second group stage]]. Dida made his first [[2000\u201301 Serie A|Serie A]] start in a 2\u20130 November loss to [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]], and was unable to beat out Rossi for the starting position after Abbiati was injured. He did not play again save for Milan's 2\u20130 loss to [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/milparigi/tutto/tutto.html|title=Sport: Galatasaray e Terim che serata per il Milan|first=Enrico|last=Curro|work=LaRepubblica.it|language=Italian|date=7 March 2001|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref>\u2014who featured his idol Taffarel in goal<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/do-you-remember/people=63514/index.html|title=Do you remember?: Taffarel|work=FIFA.com|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref>\u2014on 7 March 2001, as the ''Rossoneri'' were eliminated from the Champions League.\n\nDida returned to Milan for the [[2001\u201302 Serie A|2001\u201302 season]], for which he was later suspended by the [[Italian Football Federation]] (FIGC) for his role in a false-passport scandal and therefore loaned back to Corinthians.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/report-says-milan-fielded-ineligible-brazilian-keeper.aspx?pageID=438&n=report-says-milan-fielded-ineligible-brazilian-keeper-2000-10-31|title=Report says Milan fielded ineligible Brazilian keeper|work=Hurriyet Daily News|date= 31 October 2000|accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> He made only eight S\u00e9rie A appearances as the deputy to established first-choice [[Doni (footballer)|Doni]], but began a sustained high run of form in winning the [[Campeonato Paulista]], the [[Torneio Rio-S\u00e3o Paulo]] championship, and [[2002 Copa do Brasil]] with the ''Tim\u00e3o''.<ref name=\"acmonline\"/>\n\n====2003\u20132004: Champions League and ''Scudetto'' success====\n{{quote box|width=300px|align=right|quote=\"For me, he will always be the first companion I embraced after scoring the penalty against Buffon in that [2003] Champions League final.\"|source=\u2014[[Andriy Shevchenko]]<ref name=\"acmilanHOF\"/>}}\nDida was recalled once again by Milan for [[2002\u201303 A.C. Milan season|2002\u201303]] as a reserve, making his season debut on 14 August 2002 as an injury substitute for Christian Abbiati in the second half of Milan's [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] third-round qualifier against [[FC Slovan Liberec|Slovan Liberec]], in which his performance in the 1\u20130 victory resulted in second-year coach [[Carlo Ancelotti]] promoting him to first choice.<ref name=\"uefa305\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=279020.html|title=Dida sets the No1 example|work=uefa.com|date=8 March 2005|accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> He made a then-career best 30 starts as Milan [[2002\u201303 Serie A|finished third in Serie A]] and exhibited the league's second-best defence that conceded only 30 goals (one behind champion [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]' 29), while he won his lone [[Coppa Italia]] with the ''Rossoneri'' in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/milancop/milancop/milancop.html|title=Al Milan anche la Coppa Italia|work=LaRepubblica.it|language=Italian|date=31 May 2003|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> Dida additionally made fourteen Champions League appearances, missing only the second leg of Milan's semi-final elimination of crosstown rival [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] to injury<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=69127.html#milan+march+manchester|title=Milan march on to Manchester|work=UEFA.com|date=13 May 2003|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> as Milan advanced to face Juventus in the only [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|all-Italian final]] in competition history.\n\nDida was relatively untested during the goalless regulation and extra-time periods save for a stop of a late [[Alessandro Del Piero]] shot,<ref name=\"IOL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/sport/dida-and-shevchenko-bring-back-the-glory-days-526030|title=Dida and Shevchenko bring back the glory days|work=iol.co.za|date=29 May 2003|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> but saved from [[David Trezeguet]], [[Marcelo Zalayeta]] and [[Paolo Montero]] in the penalty shootout that saw five of the first seven shots collectively stopped by Dida and Juventus' star goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_coppe/finalissima/finalissima/finalissima.html|title=Grande Dida, coppa al Milan ma la Juve piange se stessa|work=LaRepubblica.it|language=Italian|date=28 May 2003|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/juventus/on-this-day/feature/otd-ac-milan-beat-juventus-to-win-champions-league_224012.html|title=On this day: AC Milan beat Juventus on penalties to win Champions League|first=Darren|last=Plant|work=SportsMole.co.uk|date=28 May 2015|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> After Milan's [[Andriy Shevchenko]] slotted the winner, he celebrated by leaping into Dida's arms as they were mobbed by teammates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2003/05/30/2003053338|title=AC Milan wins|work=Taipei Times|date=28 May 2003|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> Juventus coach [[Marcelo Lippi]] said after the match that \"four or five\" of his players had refused to take part in the shootout,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/may/29/newsstory.sport|title=Juventus players 'refused to take penalties'|work=The Guardian|first=Dominic|last=Fiefeld|date=28 May 2003|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> while ''Bianconeri'' defender [[Lilian Thuram]], who was not a participant, admitted to being affected beforehand by Dida's reputation as a penalty stopper.<ref name=\"IOL\"/> Dida ended the year by becoming the first Brazilian goalkeeper nominated for the [[Ballon d'Or]],<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite news | url = http://www.xtratime.org/forum/showpost.php?p=1729524&postcount=1 | title = Dida: 'I Am the Best at Nothing' | last = Penido | first = Marcos | work=[[O Globo]] (translated and reprinted on xtratime.org) | date = 16 November 2003 | accessdate =14 September 2010}}</ref> finishing 13th in voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy03.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 2003|work=rsssf.com|date=23 December 2003|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nDida became the first non-Italian [[Serie A Goalkeeper of the Year]] after conceding only 20 goals in 32 appearances in Milan's [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304]] ''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]''-winning season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200304_ufficiali.html |title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2003-04|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"scudetto\">{{cite web | url = http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2004/05/04/2003154149 | title = AC Milan takes title; Leeds slide | work=Taipei Times | date = 4 May 2004 | accessdate =22 March 2008}}</ref> Though Milan's [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] repeat bid was ended by [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]] in the quarter-finals, a highlight of their campaign was during a previous group-stage match against [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] on 16 September 2003, when Dida blocked a point blank-range shot from [[Rafael van der Vaart]] at the end of extra time to preserve Milan's 1\u20130 win.<ref name=\"ajax\">{{cite web | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/beckham-cross-sets-up-real-madrid-equaliser-87284.html | title = Beckham cross sets up Real Madrid equaliser | first=John|last=Nisbet|work=The Independent| date =16 September 2003 | accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/SPORT/09/16/grouph.milan/|title=Holders AC Milan owe it to Inzaghi|work=[[CNN.com]]|date=17 September 2003|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/18/sports/18iht-soccer_ed3__8.html|title=Soccer : Zidane shows that genius can rise above love|first=Rob|last=Hughes|work=[[NYTimes.com]]|date=18 September 2003|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132005: Internazionale flare incident and ''Miracle in Istanbul''====\nMilan started [[2004\u201305 A.C. Milan season|2004\u201305]] by winning the [[Supercoppa Italiana]], and the first half of the [[2004\u201305 Serie A|Serie A season]] saw Dida nearly insurmountable in net. After he was sent off in the ''Rossoneri's'' season opener against [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/it/news/show/184|title=MILAN-LIVORNO 2-2|work=acmilan.com|language=Italian|date=11 September 2004|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> he conceded only ten goals as Milan went unbeaten in 17 of their next 18 league matches, among them a 1\u20130 win over [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] on 28 November 2004 in which he had performed an acrobatic save on a [[Roberto Baronio]] [[Direct free kick|free kick]], changing direction after the ball was deflected midflight.<ref name=\"espngotta\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/317854/crespo-strikes-again-as-milan-win|title=Crespo strikes again as Milan win|work=ESPN|date=28 November 2004|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> Ancelotti later described the save to reporters as \"[worth] no less than a goal\".<ref name=\"espngotta\"/> Though Dida kept 16 total clean sheets and conceded 25 goals in 36 (out of 38) appearances, Milan faltered by going winless in five of their final eight matches and finished runner-up to ''Scudetto'' winners Juventus.<ref name=\"maglia0405\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200405_ufficiali.html |title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2004-05|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], Dida allowed only three goals in Milan's first ten matches, including a string of five straight clean sheets following a 2\u20131 group-stage loss to Barcelona on 2 November 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2013/m=10/news=five-classic-milan-and-barca-encounters-2200949.html|title=Five classic Milan and Barca encounters|work=FIFA.com|date=21 October 2013|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> The fifth of these came against crosstown rival [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] in the quarter-finals on 7 April 2005, in which Dida kept the ''Nerazzurri'' at bay with multiple saves, notably that of a top-corner [[Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107]] free kick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2004/matches/round=1970/match=1084880/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Mighty Milan leave rivals reeling|work=UEFA.com|date=7 April 2005|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4407905.stm|title=AC Milan 2-0 Inter Milan|work=BBC Sport|date=6 April 2005|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> With Milan leading 1\u20130 in the return leg on 12 April, Inter midfielder [[Esteban Cambiasso]]'s second-half [[Header (association football)|header]] was disallowed by referee [[Markus Merk]] due to a foul on Dida by forward [[Julio Ricardo Cruz|Julio Cruz]].<ref name=\"bbcinter\"/> Inter [[ultras]] located in the [[curva]] behind Dida's goal reacted to the call by hurling bottles and burning [[Flare (pyrotechnic)|flares]] onto the pitch.<ref name=\"bbcinter\">{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4432047.stm | title = Milan game ended by crowd trouble|publisher=BBC Sport (with photo gallery)| date= 12 April 2005 | accessdate =22 March 2008}}</ref> As Dida attempted to resume gameplay by clearing out the debris from his penalty area to take a goal kick, a flare struck him on his right shoulder, missing his head by inches.<ref name=\"bbcinter\"/> The match was halted as firefighters worked to clear the pitch while Dida received treatment for bruising and first-degree burns to his shoulder.<ref name=\"bbcinter\"/> After a half-hour delay, the game resumed with Christian Abbiati in goal but was abandoned less than a minute later after more projectiles rained down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2358092/Milan-derby-abandoned-after-flare-strikes-player.html|title=Milan derby abandoned after flare strikes player|first=Christopher|last=Davies|work=The Telegraph|date=12 April 2005|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> [[UEFA]] officially awarded Milan a 3\u20130 win, resulting in Dida tying a Champions League record, then shared with [[Edwin van der Sar]] and [[J\u00f3zef Wandzik]], with his sixth consecutive shutout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=294499.html|title=Dida aims to keep it clean|work=UEFA.com|date=12 April 2005|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Inter were later fined \u20ac200,000 (\u00a3132,000) by UEFA and ordered to play their next four European matches behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4439545.stm|title=Inter handed stadium ban and fine|work=BBC Sport|date=15 April 2005|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In the semi-finals against [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]], Dida set a competition record with his seventh consecutive clean sheet in Milan's 2\u20130 first-leg victory on 26 April,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/lehmann-looks-to-extend-individual-record|title=Lehmann looks to extend individual record|work=Arsenal.com|date=12 September 2006|accessdate=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417132553/http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/lehmann-looks-to-extend-individual-record|archive-date=17 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> but his scoreless streak ended at 623 total minutes following a [[Park Ji-sung]] strike in the ninth minute of the second leg on 4 May<ref name=\"sfinge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/img200910/uff1052_2010.pdf|title=Dida la Sfinge \u00e8 pronto a sorprendere ancora|work=[[Gazzetta dello Sport]] (reposted on magliarossonero.it) |language=Italian|date=8 December 2009|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> as PSV won 3\u20131, but the ''Rossoneri'' advanced to the final on [[Away goals rule|away goals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2004/matches/round=1971/match=1086476/postmatch/report/index.html#milan+edge+through+eindhoven|title=Milan edge through in Eindhoven|work=UEFA.com|date=5 May 2005|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nMilan charged to an early 3\u20130 lead in the first half in the [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final|2005 Champions League final]] in [[Istanbul]] against [[Premier League]] side [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], who in turn rallied in the second half with three goals in a span of six minutes, the second being a strike from Reds midfielder [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160micer]] that Dida got a hand to but was unable to keep out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esporte.uol.com.br/futebol/ultimas/2005/05/25/ult59u93729.jhtm|title=Com reviravolta, Liverpool bate o Milan e conquista a Europa|work=UOL Esporte|date=25 May 2005|accessdate=26 April 2016|language=Portuguese}}</ref> The third came on a [[Xabi Alonso]] penalty saved by Dida before Alonso netted the rebound.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/vintage-liverpool-produce-epic-response-and-triumph-in-turkey-492104.html|title=Vintage Liverpool produce epic response and triumph in Turkey|work=The Independent|first=Sam|last=Wallace|date=25 May 2005|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> With the match going to penalties after ending 3\u20133 in regulation and extra time, Dida stopped only from [[John Arne Riise]] as Liverpool won the shootout 3\u20132. He later faced press criticism for what was deemed a poor reaction to \u0160micer's shot on goal.<ref name=\"independent\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4573159.stm|title=AC Milan 3-3 Liverpool (aet)|work=BBC Sport|date=25 May 2005|accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Champions-League/25-05-2015/25-maggio-2005-milan-liverpool-3-3-sei-minuti-follia-addio-champions-110970263104.shtml|title=25 maggio 2005: Milan-Liverpool 3-3. Sei minuti di follia e addio Champions!|first=Diego|last=Mariottini|work=Gazzetta.it|language=Italian|date=25 May 2005|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> Dida was among five Milan players named to the inaugural [[FIFPro]] World XI at the end of the season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifpro.org/en/award-history/fifpro-world-xi-2004-2005|title=FIFPro World XI 2004/2005|work=fifpro.org|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> while he finished a career-best second for the 2005 IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper award, behind winner [[Petr \u010cech]] and ahead of Gianluigi Buffon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-gkoy05.html|title=IFFHS' World's Best Goalkeeper of the Year 2005|work=rsssf.com|date=28 January 2001|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> He was additionally shortlisted for the 2005 Ballon D'Or, but did not receive any votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy05.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 2005|work=rsssf.com|date=29 November 2005|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2005\u20132006: Decline in form====\nIn [[2005\u201306 A.C. Milan season|2005\u201306]], Milan went trophyless in both domestic and European competition for the first time since [[2001\u201302 A.C. Milan season|2001\u201302]]. They finished second and three points behind Juventus [[2005\u201306 Serie A|in Serie A]], before being implicated in the ''[[2006 Italian football scandal|Calciopoli]]'' [[Match fixing|match-fixing]] scandal. The ''Rossoneri'' lost as many matches (five) in the first half of the season as they had the entire previous year while conceding 22 goals in that 19-game span, with Dida not keeping a clean sheet until the fourth matchday, a 2\u20130 win over [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200506_ufficiali.html|title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2005-06|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> His form had also begun to visibly decline as he committed noticeable errors such as dropping a [[Cross (football)|cross]] in Milan's 4\u20133 win over Parma on 8 January 2006 that allowed [[Paolo Cannavaro]] to score the loose ball and give Parma an early 1\u20130 lead;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/a/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/18giornata/milanparma/milanparma.html|title=Il Milan vince con qualche brivido 4-3 al Parma e 9 punti calla Juve|work=LaRepubblica.it|language=Italian|date=8 January 2006|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> and attempting an underhand catch of an [[Andrea Gasbarroni]] shot that instead bounced off his arm and into goal, resulting in a 1\u20131 draw with [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] on 28 January that put Milan nine points behind Juventus in the title race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-01-29/title-dream-almost-over-for-ac-milan/788370|title=Title dream almost over for AC Milan|work=abc.net.au|date=28 January 2006|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> In February 2006, Brazil national team coach [[Carlos Alberto Parreira]], who had previously coached Dida at Corinthians,<ref name=\"acmonline\"/> publicly declared that Dida risked jeopardizing his starting position for the upcoming [[2006 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] if his form did not improve.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12027/2366174/dida-warned-over-form| title=Dida warned over form|first=Alex|last=Livie|publisher=Sky Sports |date=3 February 2006|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> Milan were eliminated by Barcelona in the [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final|2006 Champions League semi-final]] on a 1\u20130 aggregate, but Dida was praised for saves against [[Samuel Eto'o]], [[Ronaldinho]] and [[Henrik Larsson]] over both legs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/apr/18/minutebyminute.sport|title=Milan 0-1 Barcelona|first=Mike|last=Adamson|work=The Guardian|date= 18 April 2006|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2005/matches/round=2204/match=1107457/postmatch/report/index.html#barca+hold+firm+reach+final|title=Bar\u00e7a hold firm to reach final|work=UEFA.com|date=27 April 2006|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> However, his Champions League clean-sheet record of seven from the previous season was surpassed by [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]'s [[Jens Lehmann]], who finished the year with ten straight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/85/england/2011/03/16/2398344/the-highs-and-lows-of-jens-lehmanns-first-spell-at-arsenal|title=The Highs And Lows of Jens Lehmann's First Spell at Arsenal: From The Invincible Goalkeeper To Seeing Red in a European Final|first=Oliver|last=Yew|work=Goal.com|date=16 March 2011|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2006\u20132007: Return to Champions League victory====\n[[File:Dida 06052007.jpg|thumb|left|Dida and [[Giampaolo Pazzini]] in Milan's goalless home draw against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] on 6 May 2007]]\nAs punishment for their involvement in the 2006 ''Calciopoli'' scandal, Milan began the [[2006\u201307 Serie A]] season with an eight-point deficit in the standings, and finished fourth behind Internazionale, Roma and Lazio. Following a strike by Lazio's [[Stephen Makinwa]] in Milan's 2\u20131 season opener on 10 September 2006, Dida did not allow a league goal for the next 446 minutes.<ref name=\"stan\">{{cite web | url =http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/sa0607/spot6.html | title = Spotlight: Stan the Man| work=Football Italia | date =16 October 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710175852/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/sa0607/spot6.html |archivedate= 10 July 2007}}</ref> He played his 200th match for Milan in a 1\u20130 win over [[Ascoli Picchio F.C. 1898|Ascoli]] on 20 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/31041|title=TWO HUNDRED GAMES|work=acmilan.com|date=21 October 2006|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> However, 2006\u201307 was also the first injury-plagued season of his career, beginning with knee ligament damage suffered in Milan's 1\u20130 loss to [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]] on 21 November 2006 that sidelined him for the rest of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/ac-milan-s-dida-out-2-3-months-1.605897|title=AC Milan's Dida out 2-3 months|work=CBC Sports|date=23 November 2006|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> Reserve keeper [[Zeljko Kalac]] deputized until Dida returned on 21 January 2007 in a goalless draw with Lazio.<ref name=\"maglia0607\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200607_ufficiali.html |title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2006-07|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> He missed 13 total Serie A matches<ref name=\"maglia0607\"/> due to recurring knee and shoulder problems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/04_Aprile/16/dida.shtml|title=Milan, altro stop per Dida|work=Gazzetta.it|first=Livia|last=Taglioli|date=16 April 2007|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref> after having missed ten games in the last three seasons combined.\n\nMilan additionally had to qualify for the [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|2006\u201307 Champions League]], accomplished by defeating [[Red Star Belgrade]] on aggregate, and the ''Rossoneri'' then proceeded to top their group as Dida kept four clean sheets and conceded only twice in that six-match span.<ref name=\"maglia0607\"/> In the quarter-finals against Bayern Munich, he was criticized for conceding a stoppage-time equalizer from [[Daniel Van Buyten]] in the first leg on 3 April that relegated Milan to a 2\u20132 home draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/04_Aprile/04/ritorno.shtml|title=I mille pensieri di Ancelotti|last=di Stefano|first=Gaetano|work=Gazzetta.it|date=4 April 2007|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/milan-vicino-svolta-dida-cedere-rischia-anche-ancelotti.html|title=Milan vicino alla svolta Dida \u00e8 da cedere Rischia anche Ancelotti|first=Franco|last=Ordine|work=[[Il Giornale|IlGiornale.it]]|date=5 April 2007|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> Dida then kept a clean sheet in the second leg as Milan shut out Bayern 2\u20130 and advanced to the semi-finals against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], but he again received criticism for errors resulting in goals (from [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Wayne Rooney]]) in a 3\u20132 defeat.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/2007/05/01/dida-the-key-to-milan-champions-league-hopes/|title=Dida the key to Milan's Champions League hopes|first=James|last=Eve|work=Reuters|date=1 May 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514025251/http://blogs.reuters.com/2007/05/01/dida-the-key-to-milan-champions-league-hopes/|archivedate=14 May 2007|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref> After the loss, a Milan fan mockingly put Dida up for sale on auction site [[eBay]] before the site removed the listing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSL2772067220070427|title=Angry Milan fan puts Dida up for auction|work=Reuters|date=27 April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503023644/https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSL2772067220070427|archivedate=3 May 2007|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref> Dida kept another second-leg clean sheet in Milan's decisive 3\u20130 home win on 3 May, in addition to becoming the first goalkeeper to register an [[Assist (football)|assist]] in the Champions League,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2012/03/14/2965500/world-class-mandanda-valbuena-keep-marseilles-champions|title=World-class Mandanda & Valbuena keep Marseille\u2019s Champions League dream burning|first=Robin|last=Bairner|work=Goal.com|date=14 March 2012|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> as the ''Rossoneri'' advanced to the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final|2007 final]] for a rematch against Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6616513.stm|title=As it happened: AC Milan 3-0 Man Utd|first=Charlie|last=Henderson|date=2 May 2007|accessdate=11 May 2016}}</ref> Dida saved from [[Jermaine Pennant]], [[Steven Gerrard]] and [[Peter Crouch]] as Milan won 2\u20131 and he raised his second Champions League trophy, and the ''Rossoneri's'' seventh overall, in five seasons.<ref name=\"anfield\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anfield-online.co.uk/fixtures/2007/uefa/liverpool-1-2-ac-milan-european-cup-final.html |title=2007 CL Final Match Report |work=Anfield Online |date=23 May 2007 |accessdate=13 October 2008 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011192529/http://www.anfield-online.co.uk/fixtures/2007/uefa/liverpool-1-2-ac-milan-european-cup-final.html |archivedate=11 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====2007\u201308: Injury problems, Celtic fan incident, and benching====\nDida won his second [[2007 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] after Milan defeated [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] on 31 August 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/history/season=2007/index.html|title=2007: Milan overcome sombre Sevilla|work=UEFA.com|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> and he became the first two-time winner of the [[2007 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]] with a 4\u20132 win over [[Boca Juniors]] on 16 December.<ref name=\"lance2\">{{cite web | url = http://www.lancenet.com.br/noticias/07-12-16/208028.stm | title = Dida, o primeiro bimundial da Fifa | publisher = lancenet.com.br | date = 16 December 2007 | language = Portuguese }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He had additionally set a record with his sixth match played in the competition, a mark that was broken [[2008 FIFA Club World Cup|the next year]] when several [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] players collectively earned their seventh caps in a 1\u20130 loss to [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]].<ref name=\"fifacwc\">{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2008/m=12/news=records-rue-for-river-and-real-980345.html | title = Records to rue for River and Real | work = FIFA.com | date = 17 December 2008 | accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> Dida, however, endured his worst season with the club, as ongoing poor form and recurring injuries, including being stretchered off from the bench with [[Low back pain|lumbago]] during Milan's goalless draw at Parma on 16 February 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/feb16m.html|title=DIda injured by the bench|work=Football Italia|date=17 February 2008|accessdate=19 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302194626/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/feb16m.html|archivedate=2 March 2008}}</ref>\u2014spelled the end of his tenure as Milan's number one, while the ''Rossoneri'' finished [[2007\u201308 Serie A|fifth in Serie A]] and consequently missed out on Champions League qualification for the following season.\n\nOn 3 October 2007, during Milan's [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League group stage|Champions League group stage]] match against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in [[Glasgow]], Celtic striker [[Scott McDonald]] scored the match-winner in the 90th minute to seal a 2\u20131 victory. As the Celtic players celebrated, 27-year-old Celtic fan Robert McHendry entered the pitch and tapped Dida on the shoulder while running through Milan's penalty area. Dida initially gave chase but after a few steps collapsed to the ground while holding the side of his face, and he was stretchered off and substituted.<ref name=\"celtic1\">{{cite news | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL0344332320071003 | title = Milan won't appeal after Dida hit in Celtic win |work=Reuters | date = 3 October 2007 | accessdate =22 March 2008 | first=Kenny |last=MacDonald}}</ref> McHendry later turned himself in to police and was given a lifetime ban from [[Celtic Park]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7074557.stm|title=Service order for pitch invader|work=BBC News|date=2 November 2007|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> but UEFA charged Dida with breaching rules upholding \"loyalty, integrity and sportsmanship\", as it was deemed that he had feigned injury.<ref name=\"celtic2\"/> He was punished with a two-match suspension, while Celtic were fined \u00a325,000.<ref name=\"celtic2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/oct11n.html |title=Dida gets two-match ban |work=Football Italia |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=22 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213092607/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/oct11n.html |archivedate=13 December 2007 |url-status=dead|df=dmy }}</ref> Milan appealed the ruling, feeling the sentence \"turn[ed] Dida into the protagonist of the incident\".<ref name=\"celtic3\">{{cite web | url = http://www.espnfc.us/story/471793/dida-suspended-for-two-matches-over-fan-incident|title=Dida suspended for two matches over fan incident|work=ESPN FC |date=11 October 2007|accessdate=22 March 2008}}</ref> Dida never spoke publicly about the incident, but in Milan's first home game since the ruling, a 1\u20130 loss to [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]] on 21 October, he offered a gesture of apology to the fans by pausing during warmups to bow to each section of the crowd, receiving a round of applause in response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/05/gallerie/calcio/scuse-dida/1.html|title=Sceneggiata Glasgow, Dida chiede scusa ai tifosi (photo gallery)|work=LaRepubblica.it|language=Italian|date=21 October 2007|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"galliani\">{{cite web | url = http://www.goal.com/EN/Articolo.aspx?ContenutoId=455137 | title =  Galliani Happy To See Dida Ban Cut | publisher=Goal.com | date = 23 October 2007 | accessdate =13 October 2008}}</ref> His ban was reduced to one match, causing him to miss Milan's 4\u20131 first-leg victory over [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] on 24 October,<ref name=\"uefa\">{{cite web | url = http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/oct22g.html | title = Dida UEFA ban reduced | publisher=Channel 4 | date = 21 October 2007 | accessdate =22 March 2008 |url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071225005341/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/oct22g.html|archivedate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> but he returned for the 3\u20130 second leg victory on 6 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/shak-donetsk-vs-ac-milan/91469|title=Shak Donetsk 0-3 Milan: Inzaghi sees Milan home|work=Sky Sports|date=6 November 2016|first=Chris|last=Harvey|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> The death knell of Dida's campaign came in Milan's 2\u20131 [[Derby della Madonnina|derby]] loss to Inter on 23 December, when he inexplicably dove in the opposite direction of Esteban Cambiasso's game-winning goal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://football-italia.net/ |title=Inter 2 - 1 Milan |work=Football Italia |date=23 December 2007 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102173011/http://football-italia.net/ |archivedate=2 January 2008 }}</ref> for which he was lambasted by fans and the press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/12_Dicembre/27/frey.shtml|title=Il Milan molla Dida: Ora punta su Frey|work=Gazzetta.it|author=G.B. Olivero|language=Italian|date=27 December 2007|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/12_Dicembre/27/postdida.shtml|title=Vendesi Dida (+ Ronaldo): Sul web si digita l'ironia|work=Gazzetta.it|first=Livia|last=Taglioli|language=Italian|date=27 December 2007|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> He started Milan's 5\u20132 win over [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] on 13 January 2008, but a knee injury the following week saw him replaced by backup Zeljko Kalac, whose own strong form<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cndy/2008-02/12/content_6449328.htm|title=Ancelotti confident that Milan can leapfrog Fiorentina|work=[[China Daily]]|date=12 February 2008|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> kept him first choice for the remainder of the season, including the Champions League until Milan were eliminated in the knockout round by Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200708_ufficiali.html|title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2007-08|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> Dida's participation in the ''Goal4Africa'' charity match in [[Munich]] on 12 July 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal4africa.de/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/leaflet_final.pdf |title=Goal4Africa |language=German|accessdate=21 April 2014 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313152306/http://www.goal4africa.de/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/leaflet_final.pdf|archivedate=13 March 2016 }}</ref> marked his first gameplay of any kind since his demotion.\n\n====2008\u20132010: Revival, rivalry, and closure====\nDida was among a clog of goalkeepers on the Milan roster at the start of the [[2008\u201309 A.C. Milan season|2008\u201309 season]] that included Kalac, Abbiati, and 2007 signing [[Marco Storari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/07_Luglio/02/portieri.shtml|title=Abbiati, Dida e Kalac: Troppi per una porta|work=Gazzetta.it|first=Alessandra|last=Bocci|language=Italian|date=2 July 2008|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> With Abbiati ultimately becoming the starter, Storari being loaned out to [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], and Kalac demoted to third choice after a poor [[Russian Railways Cup]] outing against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 3 August,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/2494156/Nicolas-Anelkas-four-goals-earn-managers-praise-after-Chelsea-thrash-AC-Milan-5-0-football.html|title=Nicolas Anelka's four goals earn manager's praise after Chelsea thrash AC Milan 5-0|first=Colin|last=Spiro|work=The Telegraph|date=3 August 2008|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> Dida was designated to Milan's [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] campaign, keeping only one clean sheet in six matches as the ''Rossoneri'' were eliminated by eventual finalists [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/68/europa-league/2009/02/26/1129213/ac-milan-out-of-uefa-cup-after-werder-bremen-rally|title=AC Milan Out of UEFA Cup After Werder Bremen Rally|work=Goal.com|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> On 15 March 2009, Dida played his first Serie A match in over a year after Abbiati suffered a season-ending knee injury during Milan's 5\u20131 win at [[S.S. Robur Siena|Siena]].<ref name=\"abbiati\">{{cite web | url = http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/mar15l.html | title = Abbiati 'out for six months' | work=Football Italia|date=15 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090524173025/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/mar15l.html|archivedate=24 May 2009}}</ref> He finished the year as starter, keeping six clean sheets in a career-low ten league appearances<ref name=\"maglia0809\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200809_ufficiali.html |title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2008-09|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> as Milan placed third behind Inter and Juventus and returned to the Champions League.\n\nIn [[2009\u201310 A.C. Milan season|2009\u201310]], with Carlo Ancelotti replaced by [[Leonardo Ara\u00fajo|Leonardo]] as head coach after nine seasons, Milan finished third behind Internazionale and Juventus in [[2009\u201310 Serie A|Serie A]] for the second straight year, and were eliminated by Manchester United on a 7\u20132 aggregate in the [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] round of 16. Dida was unable to compete for the number-one jersey after missing the preseason with injury, and served as Storari's deputy until making his season debut as an injury substitute for the third time in his Milan career, in a 2\u20131 defeat of Roma on 18 October 2009.<ref name=\"storari\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2009/10/27/1586573/report-rene-higuitas-scorpion-kick-behind-milan-keeper-marco|title=Report: Rene Higuita's Scorpion Kick Behind Milan 'Keeper Marco Storari's Injury|work=Goal.com|date=27 October 2009|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> On 21 October, in his first Champions League appearance of the season against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] during the group stage, Dida caught an [[Esteban Granero]] shot in the 18th minute and hurried to move the ball upfield without having complete control of it, causing him to bounce it off his knee and [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]] to slot the loose ball into an empty net.<ref name=madrid/> His mistake did not prove costly as Madrid goalkeeper [[Iker Casillas]] erred on two goals that enabled Milan to gain their first victory (3\u20132) at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]].<ref name=madrid>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/22/champions-league-real-madrid-ac-milan|title=Pato's double rocks Real Madrid to send Milan top|work=The Guardian|first=Sid|last=Lowe|date=21 October 2009|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=300px|align=right|quote=\"Today is the first day I'm living as a former ''Rossonero'' after ten years. I wanted to ... say goodbye to all the Milan fans who in these years were close to me and with whom I have shared joys and bitterness, despite winning everything. A big thank you to [[Silvio Berlusconi]], [[Adriano Galliani]] and Sporting Director Ariedo Braida: without them I could never have had such a gratifying experience both from a sporting and human point of view. There are many people I'd like to thank: all the teammates I've had, Milan's managers and co-workers, the Milanello staff. But I especially want to cite [[Carlo Ancelotti]], the coach who allowed me to play in this fantastic team and with whom I spent the biggest part of my ''Rossoneri'' life, and [[Villiam Vecchi]], who endured me for all these years. ... Thanks from the heart and ''Forza Milan!''\"|source=\u2014Dida in his goodbye letter to Milan, 1 July 2010<ref name=\"goodbye\">{{cite web|url=http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/124235|title=THANK YOU AND FORZA MILAN!|author=Dida|work=acmilan.com|date=1 July 2010|accessdate=27 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160528020901/http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/124235|archivedate=28 May 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nDida retained the starting spot on the back of strong league performances despite Storari returning to fitness, such as a stoppage-time save from [[Pablo Granoche]] in a 25 October 2\u20131 win over Chievo,<ref name=\"chievo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italian-football/2009/10/25/1583676/chievo-12-milan-nesta-double-seals-late-diavoli-victory?ICID=AR_RS_1|title=Chievo 1\u20132 Milan: Nesta Double Seals Late Diavoli Victory|work=Goal.com|first=Stefano|last=Federici|date=25 October 2009|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> and double and triple saves performed minutes apart in a 2\u20132 draw at Napoli on 28 October.<ref name=\"napoli\">{{cite web | url = http://www.football-italia.net/sa0910/nap-mil.html | title = Napoli 2\u20132 Milan | work = Football Italia | date = 28 October 2009 | accessdate =23 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723131444/http://www.football-italia.net/sa0910/nap-mil.html|archivedate=23 July 2011}}</ref> Dida kept four clean sheets and conceded an average of one goal per game as Milan enjoyed an eight-match unbeaten league run in that stretch that ended in a 2\u20130 loss to [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]] on 13 December.<ref name=\"maglia0910\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/200910_ufficiali.html |title=AC Milan - Partite ufficiali 2009-10|work=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> With Dida retaining the number-one jersey into 2010 and Abbiati returning from injury, Storari was loaned to Sampdoria on 15 January.<ref name=\"storari2\">{{cite web|1= |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=943428.html|title=Storari joins Sampdoria on loan|work=UEFA.com|date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> However, after Abbiati returned for his first match in ten months on 31 January, a 1\u20131 draw with Livorno that Dida missed due to a back injury, both keepers were subsequently juggled in and out of the starting lineup due to Leonardo's difficulty in establishing a definite number one,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milannews.it/rassegna-stampa/dida-abbiati-ecco-come-ha-scelto-leonardo-17666|title=Dida-Abbiati: ecco come ha scelto Leonardo|work=MilanNews.it|language=Italian|first=Alessandro|last=Chiatto|date=10 February 2010|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> until Abbiati's heroics in Milan's 2\u20130 win over [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] on 21 February relegated Dida to the bench.<ref name=\"tribal\"/> Milan vice president [[Adriano Galliani]] publicly insisted that a duel between the keepers did not exist and it was Leonardo's choice whom to play.<ref name=\"tribal\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/ac-milan-chief-galliani-abbiati-will-stay-660591|title=AC Milan chief Galliani: Abbiati will stay|work=tribalfootball.com|date=23 February 2010|accessdate=13 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330011137/http://www.tribalfootball.com/ac-milan-chief-galliani-abbiati-will-stay-660591|archivedate=30 March 2010}}</ref> After Abbiati was sidelined with [[tendinitis]] on 28 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2010/03/28/1852743/milan-lose-christian-abbiati-to-injury-ahead-of-lazios-visit|title=Milan Lose Christian Abbiati To Injury Ahead of Lazio\u2019s Visit|work=Goal.com|first=Vince|last=Masiello|date=28 March 2010|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> Dida started for the rest of the season, finishing with his most Serie A appearances (23) in four years.<ref name=\"maglia0910\"/> On 1 May, he played his 300th match in all competitions for Milan in a 1\u20130 win over Fiorentina.<ref name=\"milan300\"/> He was substituted for Abbiati in the 88th minute of the ''Rossoneri's'' 3\u20130 season-finale defeat of Juventus on 15 May, receiving a standing ovation as he departed. His final games in a Milan uniform were postseason [[Exhibition match|friendlies]] against [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) teams [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] and [[Montreal Impact]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/chicago/fire/post/_/id/351/fire-find-positives-in-1-0-loss-to-milan|title=Fire find positives in 1-0 loss to Milan|work=ESPN|first=Charlie|last=Corr|date=30 May 2010|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impactmontreal.com/en/post/2010/05/30/ac-milan-confirms-its-roster|title=AC Milan confirms its roster|work=impactmontreal.com|date=30 May 2010|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> On 30 June 2010, Dida's contract expired, officially ending his decade-long tenure with the club.<ref name=\"goodbye\"/> In total, he made 302 appearances for Milan, making him the goalkeeper with the third-highest number of appearances for the club, behind only Christian Abbiati (380), and Sebastiano Rossi (330).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ilmilanista.it/news-milan/20-anni-e-150-in-rossonero-donnarumma-da-talento-a-fenomeno-con-il-milan-nel-cuore/?intcmp=donnarumma-milan |title=20 anni e 150 in rossonero: Donnarumma da talento a fenomeno, con il Milan nel cuore |publisher=ilmilanista.it |language=Italian |date=11 February 2019 |accessdate=11 February 2019 }}</ref> He finished with the currently sixth-highest number of Champions League clean sheets (35)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/7182/galleries/2015/10/21/15822242/record-holder-casillas-the-keepers-with-the-most-champions/dida-milan/16#photo|title=Record holder Casillas & the keepers with the most Champions League clean sheets|work=Goal.com|date=2015|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> and the second-highest percentage of clean sheets in games played (49%, behind Edwin Van der Sar's 52%),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2435258.html|title=Casillas and Buffon in the UEFA Champions League: Did you know?|work=UEFA.com|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> in addition to the fourth-highest unbeaten mark (623 minutes) in Champions League history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2467748.html|title=Buffon, Juventus come close to Champions League records|work=UEFA.com|date=9 May 2017|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nDida continued to participate in team-related events after his departure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Milan/20-05-2011/grandi-campi-borgonovo-801272067277.shtml|title=A San Siro per Borgonovo: Tutti uniti contro la SLA|work=Gazzetta.it|first=Gaetano|last=de Stefano|language=Italian|date=24 May 2011|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/129155|title=MILAN AND A GOOD CAUSE|work=ACMilan.com|date=17 September 2010|accessdate=2 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630122940/http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/129155|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/134473|title=FROM PARMA TO BARCELONA|work=ACMilan.com|date=10 June 2011|accessdate=1 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630084922/http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/134473|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He joined ''Milan Glorie'' (a selection of team [[Alumnus|alumni]]) for charity exhibition matches against other veterans from clubs such as [[Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi|HJK Helsinki]] and [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]], in which he was often deployed in attack instead of goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/131086|title=V\u00c9LEZ SARSFIELD - MILAN VETERANS|work=ACMilan.com|date=2 December 2010|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/135855|title=THE TOUR CONTINUES|work=ACMilan.com|date=5 September 2011|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/152818|title=MILAN GLORIE ROMP TO SUCCESS IN FINLAND|work=ACMilan.com|date=8 June 2014|accessdate=1 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630122756/http://soloperte.acmilan.com/en/news/show/152818|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In May 2012, he represented [[A.C. Milan (beach soccer)|Milan]] in the [[2012 Mundialito de Clubes|2012 ''Mundialito de Clubes'']] [[beach soccer]] tournament,<ref name=\"globoesporte_2012-05\">{{cite web | url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/eventos/futebol-de-areia/noticia/2012/05/goleiro-dida-reforca-time-do-milan-no-ii-mundialito-de-clubes-em-sao-pauloo.html | title = Goleiro Dida refor\u00e7a time do Milan no II Mundialito de Clubes em S\u00e3o Paulo | publisher=globoesporte.com | language = Portuguese|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref> in which the ''Rossoneri'' were eliminated in the group stage after going winless in three games.\n\n===Return to Brazil===\n\n====Portuguesa (2012)====\nAfter two years of being unable to secure a contract and continue playing in Europe, Dida returned to Brazil to resume his career.<ref name=\"fifaprep\"/> On 24 May 2012, [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]] signed him for the remainder of the season as a replacement for departing goalkeeper [[W\u00e9verton Pereira da Silva|W\u00e9verton]].<ref>{{cite news | date= 23 December 2011| url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/portuguesa/noticia/2012/05/portuguesa-acerta-contratacao-do-ex-aposentado-dida.html | title=Portuguesa anuncia acordo com Dida e tira goleiro da aposentadoria|work=[[Rede Globo|GloboEsporte]]| language = Portuguese|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref> He made his debut on 26 June in a 1\u20130 win over S\u00e3o Paulo,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/jogo/brasileirao2012/23-06-2012/portuguesa-sao-paulo.html|title=Na estr\u00e9ia de Dida, Lusa vence no Canind\u00e9 e aumenta crise no Tricolor|first=Marcelo|last=Prado|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> and on 1 July, helped in holding [[Santos FC|Santos]] to a goalless draw in a match that was billed as a duel of generations between Dida and Santos' young star [[Neymar]], who was 18 years his junior.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/brasileirao-serie-a/noticia/2012/07/portuguesa-pressiona-mas-so-empata-sem-gols-com-o-santos.html|title=Portuguesa encurrala o Santos, mas cl\u00e1ssico no Canind\u00e9 termina zerado|first=Marcelo|last=Hazan|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=1 July 2012|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/brasileirao-serie-a/noticia/2012/07/portuguesa-x-santos-marca-duelo-de-geracoes-entre-dida-e-neymar.html|title=Portuguesa x Santos marca duelo de gera\u00e7\u00f5es entre Dida e Neymar|date=1 July 2012|accessdate=5 June 2016|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Dida made 32 starts and conceded 31 goals as Portuguesa avoided relegation from the Campeonato Brasileiro top flight, but he departed at the end of the season after his contract expired in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/portuguesa/noticia/2012/12/presidente-da-portuguesa-coloca-goleiro-dida-no-gremio-em-2013.html|title=Presidente da Portuguesa coloca goleiro Dida no Gr\u00eamio em 2013|first=Alexandre|last=Lozetti|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=3 December 2012|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Gr\u00eamio (2013)====\nOn 19 December 2012, Dida joined [[Porto Alegre]]-based [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] on a deal for an undisclosed duration, which was finalized after he accepted a reduction of his original wage request.<ref name=\"SF-GFB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sambafoot.com/en/news/40490_done_deal__gremio_announce_dida_signing.html|title=Gr\u00eamio announce Dida signing|first=Christopher|last=Atkins|work=Sambafoot.com|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref> He was signed at the behest of coach [[Vanderlei Luxemburgo]], who sought an experienced backup to incumbent [[Marcelo Grohe]].<ref name=\"SF-GFB\"/> By January 2013, Dida had surpassed the 26-year-old Grohe as first choice, making 37 league starts and allowing 34 goals as Gr\u00eamio [[2013 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|finished runner-up]] to Cruzeiro, while advancing to the semi-final of the [[2013 Copa do Brasil|Copa do Brasil]] by eliminating Corinthians in a penalty shootout that saw Dida stop three spot kicks, notably former Milan teammate [[Alexandre Pato]]'s botched [[Panenka (penalty kick)|panenka]] attempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-za/news/4563/main/2013/10/26/4360288/i-wasnt-careless-pato|title=Pato denies negligence after penalty miss|work=Goal.com|first=Alex|last=Moretto|date=26 October 2013|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> Gr\u00eamio were unable to advance past the round of 16 in the [[2013 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]] after losing on away goals to [[Independiente Santa Fe]], which led to Luxemburgo's firing on 30 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/792580.shtml|title=Former Real Madrid boss Luxemburgo sacked by Gremio|author=Xinhua|work=Global Times|date=30 June 2013|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Internacional (2013\u20132015)====\nWith Gr\u00eamio turning down his extension request at the end of the season, Dida signed a two-year deal with archrival [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]] on 26 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sambafoot.com/en/news/55186_international_announce_signing_of_dida_and_wellington_paulista_for_2014.html|title=International announce signing of Dida and Wellington Paulista for 2014|first=Georges|last=Sessions|work=Sambafoot.com|date=26 December 2013|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref> He downplayed the rivalry between the clubs, citing that he had wanted to remain in Porto Alegre for family reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rs/futebol/times/internacional/noticia/2013/12/dida-agradece-confianca-do-inter-e-ve-saida-do-gremio-como-novo-desafio.html|title=Dida agradece confian\u00e7a do Inter e v\u00ea sa\u00edda do Gr\u00eamio como novo desafio| first=Tom\u00e1s|last=Hammes|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=26 December 2013|accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> Due to injury, Dida did not make his debut until 23 February 2014 in a 1\u20130 loss to [[Veran\u00f3polis Esporte Clube Recreativo e Cultural|Veran\u00f3polis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sambafoot.com/en/news/57216_world_cup_winner_dida_still_not_ready_for_internacional_debut.html|title=World Cup winner Dida still not ready for Internacional debut|first=Stuart|last=MacLennan|work=Sambafoot.com|date=18 February 2014|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esportes.estadao.com.br/noticias/futebol,internacional-perde-a-primeira-no-gauchao-na-estreia-de-dida,1133729|title=Internacional perde a primera no Gauch\u00e3o na estreia de Dida|work=esportes.estadao.com.br|language=Portuguese|date=23 February 2014|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref> but was able to supplant brothers [[Alisson (footballer, born 1992)|Alisson]] and [[Muriel Gustavo Becker|Muriel]] for the starting spot, making 27 total first-team appearances as Internacional would finish [[2014 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|third in S\u00e9rie A]] and win the [[2014 Campeonato Ga\u00facho]]. However, following a poor performance in a 2\u20130 loss to his former club Vit\u00f3ria on 10 September,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esporte.uol.com.br/futebol/campeonatos/brasileiro/serie-a/ultimas-noticias/2014/09/10/vitoria-x-internacional.htm|title=Dida falha, Inter perde para o Vit\u00f3ria por 2 a 0 e confirma m\u00e1 fase|work=UOL Esporte|language=Portuguese|date=10 September 2014|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> Dida was benched in favor of Muriel for Internacional's 2\u20130 win over [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]] four days later, but entered as an injury substitute in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.correiodopovo.com.br/Esportes/?Noticia=535700|title=Inter faz 2 a 0 no Botafogo e se mant\u00e9m no G4|work=Correio do Povo|first=Cristiano|last= Munari |language=Portuguese|date=14 September 2014|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe made six consecutive starts while Muriel recovered from a thigh injury, but lost the job permanently after Internacional were blown out 5\u20130 by [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Chapecoense de Futebol|Chapecoense]] on 5 October, during which he was [[Penalty card#red card|sent off]] for a [[Off the ball|late challenge]].<ref name=\"8meses\"/> Alisson was established as the ''Colorado's'' number one thereafter,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diariodaregiao.com.br/esportes/em-um-ano-alisson-passa-de-promessa-a-goleiro-titular-da-sele\u00e7\u00e3o-brasileira-1.409696|title=Em um ano, Alisson passa de promessa a goleiro titular da sele\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira|first=Daniel|last=Batista|language=Portuguese|work=Diario da Regi\u00e3o|date=23 March 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> with Dida demoted to third choice. His final match was a 2\u20130 win over [[Esporte Clube Passo Fundo|Passo Fundo]] on 5 April 2015 in the first round of the [[2015 Campeonato Ga\u00facho]],<ref name=\"8meses\">{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rs/futebol/times/internacional/noticia/2015/12/de-saida-do-inter-dida-faz-apenas-um-jogo-em-2015-e-fica-8-meses-sem-atuar.html|title=De sa\u00edda do Inter, Dida faz apenas um jogo em 2015 e fica 8 meses sen atuar|work=GloboEsporte|first= Tom\u00e1s|last=Hammes|language=Portuguese|date=7 December 2015|accessdate=12 June 2016}}</ref> a match in which he became the oldest player, at 41 years and six months, to ever take the pitch for Internacional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wp.clicrbs.com.br/centraldeesportes/2015/04/08/dida-e-o-jogador-mais-velho-a-vestir-a-camisa-do-inter-na-historia/?topo=52,1,1,,171,e171|title=Dida \u00e9 o jogador mais velho a vestir a camisa do Inter na hist\u00f3ria|work=Central de Esportes|first=Raphael|last=Gomes|language=Portuguese|date=5 April 2015|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> On 25 August, an online video of Dida performing a series of acrobatic practice saves during a team training session went [[Viral video|viral]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/41-year-old-dida-does-an-amazing-goalkeeper-exercise-in-internacional-training-video/|title=41-year-old Dida does an amazing goalkeeper exercise in Internacional training (Video)|first=Dov|last=Rawson|work=101greatgoals.com|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/video/video-follie/2015/08/25-3458979/ve_lo_ricordate_dida_a_41_anni_vola_ancora_tra_i_pali/|title=Ve lo ricordate Dida? A 41 anni vola ancora tra i pali|work=[[Tuttosport|tuttosport.it]]|language=Italian|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elconfidencial.com/multimedia/video/deportes/futbol/internacional/2015-08-25/41-years-old-nelson-dida-shows-unbelievable-endurance-and-athleticism-on-training_986469/|title=As\u00ed se entrena Dida... a sus 41 a\u00f1os|work=[[El Confidencial|elconfidencial.com]]|language=Spanish|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstalk.com/WATCH:-One-former-international-goalkeeper-in-his-forties-is-as-agile-as-ever|title=WATCH: One former international goalkeeper in his forties is as agile as ever|first=Daniel|last=Kelly|work=newstalk.com|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=15 June 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDida temporarily remained with the club in an internship role after his contract expired, as he began studying to earn his coaching badges. He took [[Brazilian Football Confederation]]-required courses in [[Teres\u00f3polis]] in December 2015 alongside former Brazil teammates Taffarel and Ricardinho,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/cruzeiro/noticia/2015/12/deivid-esta-em-teresopolis-no-rio-onde-participa-de-curso-de-tecnicos.html|title=Agora efetivado, Deivid participa de curso com outros t\u00e9cnicos brasileiros|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=14 December 2015|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> and watched Internacional's training sessions under the observation of then-current manager [[Argel Fucks]] in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wp.clicrbs.com.br/grenal/2016/02/15/estudando-para-ser-tecnico-dida-cumpre-periodo-no-inter-como-observador-de-argel/?topo=52,1,1,,171,77|title=Estudando para ser t\u00e9cnico, Dida cumpre per\u00edodo no Inter como observador de Argel|first=Rodrigo|last=Oliveira|work=wp.clicrbs.com.br|language=Portuguese|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, he told ''[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]'' that he planned on continuing his studies in Italy through the following year, and expressed a desire to coach Milan in the future.<ref name=\"GDScoach\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzettaworld.com/interview/dida-future-milan-coaching-role/|title=Interview: Dida targets future AC Milan coaching role|first=Alessandra|last=Gozzini|work=gazzettaworld.com|date=23 April 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> On 9 June, Dida declared that he was not retired and was in search of a new club with whom to finish his playing career,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.uol.com.br/video/605152_dida-elogia-grande-potencial-de-alisson-e-pede-clube-para-encerrar-carreira|title=Dida elogia 'grande potencial' de Alisson e pede clube para encerrar carreira|work=ESPN Brasil|language=Portuguese|date=9 June 2016|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> but he received no offers. From October to December 2016, he served as an assistant and consultant to [[China League One]] club [[Shenzhen F.C.|Shenzhen]] under the invitation of then-head coach [[Clarence Seedorf]] until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chinabrasilfutebol.com.br/noticias/a-experiencia-de-dida-na-china|title=A experi\u00eancia de Dida na China|trans-title=Dida's experience in China|first=Rodolfo|last=Mohr|work=China Brasile Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===1993\u20131996: Youth career, first cap, and Olympics disappointment===\nDida is the first major Brazilian goalkeeper to be known by a nickname, as opposed to the tradition of going by either his first or last name.<ref name=\"futebol\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2006/06/why_ronaldinho_has_no_last_name.html|title=How Brazilian soccer players get their names|first=Nick|last=Schulz|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate.com]]|date=10 June 2006|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> He first represented the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' at the [[Brazil national under-20 football team|under-20]] level as first choice at the [[1993 FIFA World Youth Championship]], keeping four clean sheets in six matches and conceding only two goals as Brazil were victorious.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/news/y=2007/m=3/news=australia-1993-brazil-make-three-501763.html|title=Australia 1993: Brazil make it three|work=FIFA.com|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> After Taffarel was suspended for the first two games of the [[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] due to a uniform violation,<ref name=\"desafia\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/1995/7/07/esporte/4.html|title=Dida desafia mito do goleiro negro na sele\u00e7\u00e3o|trans-title=Dida challenges the myth of black goalkeepers for the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o''|first1=Fernando|last1=Rodrigues|first2=M\u00e1rio|last2=Magalh\u0101es|work=Folha de S.Paulo|language=Portuguese|date=7 July 1995|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> Dida earned his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for the senior side at age 21 in a 1\u20130 defeat of [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]],<ref name=\"rsssf\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/dida-intl.html | title = Nelson de Jes\u00fas Silva \"Dida\" \u2013 International Appearances | publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate =1 June 2009}}</ref> and started in Brazil's 2\u20130 win over [[Peru national football team|Peru]].\n\nHe was called up by coach [[M\u00e1rio Zagallo]] as the backup to [[Danrlei]] for the [[1996 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], in which Brazil sent their [[Brazil national under-23 football team|under-23]] squad, and he never left the bench as the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' finished runners-up to [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]. Dida was named the starter for the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]], but Brazil endured a disappointing campaign and finished with a bronze medal, while he gained notoriety for colliding with teammate [[Aldair]] in a 1\u20130 loss to [[Japan national football team|Japan]] as they chased a long ball into the penalty area, giving Japan the empty-net goal.<ref name=\"acmonline\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-07-22/news/ss-26862_1_teruyoshi-ito|title=Brazil Ambushed by Upstart Japan, 1-0|work=latimes.com|date=22 July 1996|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===1997\u20132001: First World Cup, and Copa Am\u00e9rica success===\n{{quote box|width=27%|align=right|quote=\"He will dominate the [goalkeeping] position for many years. I pray that God will protect him.\"|source=\u2014Former Brazil goalkeeper [[Moacir Barbosa Nascimento|Moacyr Barbosa]] on Dida before the [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica Final|1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica final]].<ref name=\"barbosa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diariodecuiaba.com.br/arquivo/180799/esportes2.htm|title=Barbosa confia em Dida|trans-title=Barbosa trusts Dida|work=Diario de Cuiaba|language=Portuguese|date=July 1999|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref>}}\nDida was excluded from Brazil's [[1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] roster, but returned to the starting lineup for the inaugural [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup|FIFA Confederations Cup]] that year, keeping five clean sheets and allowing just two total goals as the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' lifted the trophy with a [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|6\u20130 rout]] of [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] in the final. Though he was called up for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] in [[France]], Zagallo lured Taffarel out of a three-year retirement to be his first choice, and Dida was third behind backup [[Carlos Germano]] as Brazil [[1998 FIFA World Cup Final|finished runners-up]] to [[France national football team|the hosts]]. He would not play for the national team in all of 1998,<ref name=\"rsssf\"/> which factored into his decision to leave club team Cruzeiro for Milan at the start of the next year.<ref name=\"placar899\"/> In 1999, under new coach Vanderlei Luxemburgo, Dida won his lone [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica|Copa Am\u00e9rica]] with Brazil after a 3\u20130 defeat of [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in the final. He conceded only two total goals, while stopping a game-tying [[Roberto Ayala]] penalty in a 2\u20131 victory over archrival [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/12/sports/plus-soccer-missed-penalty-kick-dooms-argentina.html|title=Missed Penalty Kick Dooms Argentina|work=NYTimes.com|date=12 July 1999|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> He made his second straight [[1999 FIFA Confederations Cup|Confederations Cup]] start that year as Brazil allowed no goals in the group stage and thrashed hosts [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] 8\u20132 in the semi-finals, but were again thwarted by champions Mexico, losing 4\u20133 in [[1999 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|the final]].\n\nUnder the helm of [[\u00c9merson Le\u00e3o]], his third ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' head coach in six years, Dida started his third consecutive Confederations Cup in [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup|2001]], keeping clean sheets in every group stage match for the second consecutive time as Brazil finished second behind Japan with one win and two draws, but lost to eventual winners France 2\u20131 in the semi-finals and, subsequently, 1\u20130 to Australia in the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup#Third place play-off|third-place match]].\n\n===2002\u20132005: World Cup triumph and Confederations Cup record===\n[[File:Dida.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Dida (seen here in 2005) earned 91 caps with [[Brazilian national football team|Brazil]] from 1995 to 2006, and was part of three [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] squads.]]\nWith his success at Corinthians gaining the attention of [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]], who had replaced Luxemburgo following Brazil's lackluster qualification, Dida was called up for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] held jointly in [[South Korea]] and Japan, as the backup to [[Marcos Roberto Silveira Reis|Marcos]], whom Scolari had previously coached at Palmeiras. Dida and third-choice [[Rog\u00e9rio Ceni]] never left the bench as the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' won its [[FIFA World Cup Trophy|fifth trophy]] with a [[2002 FIFA World Cup Final|2\u20130 defeat]] of [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref name=\"acmonline\"/> On the afternoon of the final, Dida was requested by [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] to keep him company in hopes of avoiding a repeat of the events prior to the 1998 final, when Ronaldo had suffered a [[Epileptic seizure|convulsive fit]] in his sleep that factored into his poor performance in Brazil's loss.<ref name=\"acmonline\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/history/newsid_1749000/1749324.stm|title=The great World Cup Final mystery |work=BBC Sport |date=2 April 2002 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xtratime.org/forum/1220166-post107.html|title=I need more time, insists Ronaldo|work=ESPN Soccernet (reprinted on xtratime.org) |date=17 November 2002|accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref> They spent the time talking and playing golf before departing for [[International Stadium Yokohama|International Stadium]] in [[Yokohama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Estero/06-10-2010/tutta-ronaldo-story-711376709871.shtml|title=Tutta la Ronaldo Story: La biografia non-autorizzata|work=Gazzetta.it|language=Italian|author=Gasport|date=7 October 2010|accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref> Ronaldo scored both goals in the 2002 victory and won the tournament's [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|Golden Shoe]] award.\n\nDida started his fourth [[2003 FIFA Confederations Cup|Confederations Cup]] in 2003, but Brazil suffered its worst-ever finish by being eliminated in the group stage. He did not participate in any international tournaments in 2004, but returned for a fifth and last Confederations Cup start [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|in 2005]] at age 31, making him the oldest member of Brazil's [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup squads#Brazil|starting roster]]. In a 1\u20130 group stage loss to Mexico on 19 June 2005, he saved a penalty from [[Jared Borgetti]] that had to be retaken twice due to repeated player encroachment into the penalty area, after Borgetti scored on the first attempt but hit the crossbar on the second.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/335772/borgetti-relieved-after-penalty-woes|title=Borgetti relieved after penalty woes|first=Mike|last=Collett|work=ESPN FC|date=20 June 2005|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref> Dida was rested by coach Carlos Alberto Parreira for a 2\u20132 draw with Japan on 22 June as Marcos earned his final cap for Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2005/06/22/zico-sticks-misfiring-pair|title=Zico sticks with misfiring pair|author=PA Sport|work=theworldgame.sbs.com.au|date=22 June 2005|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> In a 3\u20132 semifinal victory over hosts Germany, he faced his second penalty of the competition, which [[Michael Ballack]] converted despite Dida guessing the right direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/en/news/detail/fifa-confederations-cup-host-germany-lose-2-3-against-brazil-4615/|title=FIFA CONFEDERATIONS CUP: HOST GERMANY LOSE 2-3 AGAINST BRAZIL|work=dfb.de|date=26 June 2005|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref> He became the first two-time Confederations Cup winner after the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o's'' decisive 4\u20131 win over Argentina in the final, which would be the last trophy of his international career.<ref name=\"fifacc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/statistics/news/newsid=1070364.html#south+africa+2009+numbers |title=South Africa 2009 in numbers |publisher=FIFA |date=12 June 2009 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618165441/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/statistics/news/newsid%3D1070364.html#south+africa+2009+numbers |archivedate=18 June 2009  }}</ref>\n\n===2006 World Cup and international retirement===\nAfter 86 caps earned and two World Cups as an unplayed reserve,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/internacional/en/sports/worldcup/2014/06/1469108-neymar-is-brazils-most-experienced-player-at-world-cups.shtml|title=2014 World Cup: Neymar is Brazil's Most Experienced Player |first=Juliana|last=Calderari|work=folha.uol.com.br|date=12 June 2014|accessdate=12 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410031801/https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/internacional/en/sports/worldcup/2014/06/1469108-neymar-is-brazils-most-experienced-player-at-world-cups.shtml|url-status=live|archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Dida started the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] finals in Germany, making him the second-oldest World Cup goalkeeper for Brazil, at 32 years and eight months, behind [[Gylmar dos Santos Neves|Gilmar]] (35 years in [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]]).<ref name=\"folha\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/esporte/fk1106200606.htm|title=Dida quebra tabus na sele\u00e7\u00e3o|trans-title=Dida breaks taboos for Sele\u00e7\u00e3o|author=Eduardo Arruba|display-authors=et al|language=Portuguese|work=Folha de S.Paulo|date=11 June 2006|accessdate=13 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410025733/https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/esporte/fk1106200606.htm|url-status=live|archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref> He was part of Brazil's unheralded defensive unit,<ref name=\"malta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20060629/football/ronaldo-grabs-headlines-defenders-do-the-work.49859|title=Ronaldo grabs headlines, defenders do the work|author=Reuters|work=[[Times of Malta|timesofmalta.com]]|date=29 June 2006|accessdate=1 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410031236/https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/ronaldo-grabs-headlines-defenders-do-the-work.49859|url-status=live|archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"assistants\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/371761/the-magicians-assistants|title=The magicians' assistants|first=Andrew|last=Downie|work=[[ESPN FC]]|date=19 June 2006|accessdate=7 July 2016}}{{dead link|date=April 2020|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> with [[L\u00facio]] and [[Juan Silveira dos Santos|Juan]], that conceded only one goal in wins over [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], Australia and Japan in the group stage. In a 3-0 round-of-sixteen victory over [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], Dida performed a point-blank save from [[John Mensah]] with his leg,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/27/AR2006062700851_pf.html|title=Brazil Wins Behind Ronaldo's Record Goal|first=Tales|last=Azzoni|work=The Washington Post|date=27 June 2006|accessdate=7 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410032117/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/27/AR2006062700851_pf.html|url-status=live|archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref> and was [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]] winner [[Tost\u00e3o]]'s personal choice for man of the match.<ref name=\"malta\"/> However, Brazil struggled offensively throughout and were eliminated after a 1-0 loss to France in [[2006 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Quarter-finals|the quarter-finals]], with Dida and the defense among the few players avoiding media criticism for the team's disappointing performance.<ref name=\"sempretrio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/todas/2006/07/01/223757/brasilenos-enmudecieron-tras-quedar-eliminados-del-mundial.html|title=Brasile\u00f1os enmudecieron tras quedar eliminados del Mundial|trans-title=Brazilians fall silent after World Cup elimination|language=Spanish|work=Emol.com|date=1 July 2006|accessdate=8 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410034811/https://www.emol.com/noticias/todas/2006/07/01/223757/brasilenos-enmudecieron-tras-quedar-eliminados-del-mundial.html|url-status=live|archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2008/11/goalkeepers_from_brazil.html|title=In defense of Brazilian goalkeepers|first=Tim|last=Vickery|work=BBC.co.uk|date=17 November 2008|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> He became the first keeper to wear the [[Captain (association football)|captain's armband]] for Brazil, since \u00c9merson Le\u00e3o in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]], when [[Cafu]] was rested in the 4\u20131 win over Japan on 22 June.<ref name=\"globocaptain\">{{cite news|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/ESP/Noticia/Arquivo/0,,AA1221920-4482,00-SEM+CAFU+DIDA+E+O+NOVO+CAPITAO+DA+SELECAO.html|title=Sem Cafu, Dida \u00e9 o novo capit\u00e3o da sele\u00e7\u00e3o|trans-title=Without Cafu, Dida is the new national team captain|publisher=[[Globo Esporte]]|language=Portuguese|last=Ianacca|first=M\u00e1rcio|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=14 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410034014/http://globoesporte.globo.com/ESP/Noticia/Arquivo/0,,AA1221920-4482,00-SEM+CAFU+DIDA+E+O+NOVO+CAPITAO+DA+SELECAO.html|url-status=live|archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDida did not play for Brazil again following the July 2006 hiring of new coach [[Dunga]], and retired from the national team on 1 October.<ref name=\"nzherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/event/story.cfm?c_id=524&ObjectID=10403911 | title=Dida calls it a day for Brazil|author=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=29 December 2006|accessdate=22 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014514/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/event/story.cfm?c_id=524&ObjectID=10403911|url-status=dead|archivedate=30 September 2007}}</ref> He finished with 91 total caps, ranking third all-time among Brazilian keepers behind Taffarel (101) and Gilmar (94), while allowing 70 goals. He is currently the most successful player in the history of the Confederations Cup, ranking first in appearances (22)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2017/m=4/news=mixed-memories-for-confeds-record-breaker-dida-2880445.html|title=Mixed memories for Confeds record-breaker Dida|work=[[FIFA]]|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> and clean sheets (12),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2017/m=5/news=12-days-to-go-unbeatable-dida-s-outstanding-record-2884482.html|title=12 days to go: Unbeatable Dida's outstanding record|work=UEFA.com|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> while being the only player to participate in five editions of the competition.<ref name=\"fifacc\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/|title=FIFA Tournaments: Players & Coaches (Confederations Cup)|work=FIFA.com|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> Dida faced a total of eight penalties in his international career, saving six of them.<ref name=\"manual\">{{cite news|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/ESP/Noticia/Arquivo/0,,AA1223336-5187,00-O+MANUAL+DE+PEGADOR+DE+PENALTIS+POR+DIDA.html|title=O manual de pegador de p\u00eanaltis, por Dida|work=GloboEsporte.com|language=Portuguese|last=Gonzalez|first=Ricardo|date=24 June 2006|accessdate=14 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014063048/http://globoesporte.globo.com/ESP/Noticia/Arquivo/0,,AA1223336-5187,00-O+MANUAL+DE+PEGADOR+DE+PENALTIS+POR+DIDA.html|url-status=dead|archivedate=14 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play and reception==\nAlthough he is regarded by several pundits as one of the best goalkeepers of his generation,<ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\"/><ref name=\"foxsports\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/gallery/champions-league-best-goalkeepers-ever-neuer-buffon-cech-van-der-sar-casillas-031417|title=The 10 best goalkeepers in Champions League history|first=Thomas|last=Hautmann|work=[[Fox Sports]]|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> and as one of Brazil's greatest goalkeepers ever,<ref name=\"Brazil's 10 Best Goalkeepers\"/> Dida has received a divided response to his playing style, particularly during his time with Milan,<ref name=\"trionfi\"/><ref name=\"sudamerica\"/> where he was noted for excelling as a Brazilian goalkeeper in a country (Italy) renowned for producing quality keepers.<ref name=\"surgiu\"/><ref name=\"reuters\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegentlemanultra.com/when-calcio-ruled-the-world/when-calcio-ruled-the-wolrd-walter-zenga|title=When Calcio Ruled the World: Walter Zenga|first=Richard|last=Hall|work=thegentlemanultra.com|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=18 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006015325/http://www.thegentlemanultra.com/when-calcio-ruled-the-world/when-calcio-ruled-the-wolrd-walter-zenga|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He trained extensively with ''Rossoneri'' goalkeeping coach [[Villiam Vecchi]], who had previously tutored [[Gianluigi Buffon]] at Parma.<ref name=\"trionfi\"/><ref name=\"marca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/07/15/en/football/real_madrid/1373904063.html|title=Real Madrid signs top goalkeeping coach|work=marca.com|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"portiere\">{{cite web|url=http://ilportiere.com/news/william-vecchi-ho-allenato-dida-e-buffon-sono-incredibili.html|title=William Vecchi: 'Ho allenato Dida e Buffon: sono incredibili'|trans-title=William Vecchi: \"I trained Dida and Buffon: they're incredible\"|work=ilportiere.com|language=Italian|date=2 December 2004|accessdate=16 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916123402/http://ilportiere.com/news/william-vecchi-ho-allenato-dida-e-buffon-sono-incredibili.html|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Vecchi described Dida as \"more reflective\" in his gameplay, whereas Buffon acted mainly on instinct.<ref name=\"portiere\"/> In his prime, Dida was recognized for his shot-stopping ability and command of the area,<ref name=\"penpics\"/> and for possessing athleticism and reflexes that belied his imposing size,<ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\"/><ref name=\"fifaprep\"/><ref name=\"acmonline\"/> which enabled him to perform acrobatic \"miracle\" saves without resorting to histrionics,<ref name=\"maidire\"/><ref name=\"90min\"/> while former coaches have praised him for keeping his emotions in check after conceding a goal.<ref name=\"espngotta\"/><ref name=\"oglobo\"/> Dida's best-known attribute is his expertise in saving penalties,<ref name=\"fifaprep\"/><ref name=\"manual\"/> which is acknowledged mainly in Brazil due to his accomplishments with Corinthians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rs/noticia/2013/10/lista-relembra-14-defesas-de-dida-em-cobrancas-de-penaltis-em-16-anos.html|title=Lista relembra defesas marcantes de Dida em cobran\u00e7as de p\u00eanaltis|language=Portuguese|work=Globo Esporte|date=25 October 2013|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ndonline.com.br/florianopolis/esportes/114301-com-sete-penaltis-agarrados-no-timao-dida-agora-e-a-esperanca-gremista.html|title=Com sete p\u00eanaltis agarrados no Tim\u00e3o, Dida agora \u00e9 a esperan\u00e7a gremista|work=Lance!Net|language=Portuguese|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=18 August 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://torcedores.com/noticias/2015/04/relembre-penaltis-defendidos-por-dida-em-momentos-decisivos|title=Relembre p\u00eanaltis defendidos por Dida em momentos decisivos|first=Felipe|last=Chegan|work=torcedores.com|language=Portuguese|date=15 April 2015|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> He is additionally recognized for his reserved disposition both on and off the pitch and his reluctance in granting interviews,<ref name=\"sfinge\"/><ref name=\"reuters\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milannews24.com/nelson-dida-eroe-muto/|title=Nelson Dida, un eroe muto|trans-title=Nelson Dida, mute hero|work=milannews24.com|language=Italian|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"jefferson\">{{cite web|url=http://esportes.opovo.com.br/app/esportes/clubes/botafogo/2012/11/04/noticiasbotafogo,2458777/jefferson-revela-que-dida-foi-espelho-no-inicio-de-carreira-dele.shtml|title=Jefferson revela que Dida foi espelho no in\u00edcio de carreira dele|trans-title=Jefferson reveals that he mirrored Dida early in his career|work=esportes.opovo.com.br|date=4 November 2012|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/ESP/Noticia/Futebol/Campeonatos/0,,MUL420238-8068,00.html|title=Avesso \u00e0 fama, Aranha vive '\u00e0 la Dida'|trans-title=Averse to fame, Aranha lives '\u00e0 la Dida'|first=Leandro|last=Can\u00f4nico|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=22 April 2008|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> as well as his physical conditioning and work ethic.<ref name=\"fifaprep\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Inter se anima com preparo de Dida, e goleiro vira exemplo|url=http://www.tribunahoje.com/noticia/90634/esporte/2014/01/14/inter-se-anima-com-preparo-de-dida-e-goleiro-vira-exemplo.html|language=Portuguese|work=Tribuna Hoje|date=14 January 2014|accessdate=27 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826140752/http://www.tribunahoje.com/noticia/90634/esporte/2014/01/14/inter-se-anima-com-preparo-de-dida-e-goleiro-vira-exemplo.html|archive-date=26 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDida, however, has also faced criticism for lapses in concentration that sometimes resulted in mistakes or goals, with the Leeds goal from 2000 remaining his most prominent example.<ref name=\"espngotta\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/story/688027/worst-goalkeeping-errors|title=Worst goalkeeping errors|date=21 October 2009|work=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/18/newsstory.sport3|title=Great goalkeeping blunders of recent times|work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2001|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref> He has been scrutinized for suspect footwork,<ref name=\"sai\">{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/bomdiabrasil/0,,MUL815451-16020,00-SAI+QUE+E+SUA+DIDA.html|title=Sai que \u00e9 sua, Dida!|trans-title=Get what's yours, Dida!|work=g1.globo.com|language=Portuguese|date=3 February 2006|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> hesitance in coming off his [[Football pitch#Penalty and goal areas|goalline]],<ref name=\"espngotta\"/><ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\"/><ref name=\"acmonline\"/> and fielding [[Cross (football)|crosses]].<ref name=\"maidire\"/><ref name=\"Fenomeno Dida, un felino tra i pali il portiere che sembrava un bidone\"/><ref name=\"trionfi\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballitaliano.co.uk/p6_66_1147_lessons-in-calcio-walter-zenga.html#.V4cDw-lOTzJ|title=Lessons in Calcio: Walter Zenga|first=Richard|last=Hall|work=footballitaliano.co.uk|date=24 March 2010|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> He was considered one of the world's best goalkeepers at the height of his success with Milan from 2003 to 2005, including a perceived rivalry with Buffon as the best overall in world football,<ref name=\"maidire\"/><ref name=\"trionfi\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballitaliano.co.uk/p6_66_277_club-focus-roma-requiem-for-a-dream.html#.V6LGK-lOTzJ|title=Club Focus - Roma - Requiem for a dream|first=Andrea|last=Tallarita|work=footballitaliano.co.uk|date=15 April 2009|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> but the April 2005 Internazionale flare incident is widely cited as the catalyst behind the end of his high run of form.<ref name=\"espngotta\"/><ref name=\"maidire\"/><ref name=\"ultimouomo\"/><ref name=\"milannews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.milannews.it/news/dida-tra-miracoli-e-papere-otto-anni-in-rossonero-24944/|title=Dida: tra miracoli e papere, otto anni in rossonero|first=Pietro|last=Mazzara|language=Italian|work=milannews.it|date=17 May 2010|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> In 2006, ''[[The Guardian]]'' labeled Dida \"Brazil's answer to [[David James (footballer)|David James]]\", who himself had gained infamy for goalkeeping errors while playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jan/31/europeanfootball.sport|title=Milan strangled by another half-Nelson|first=James|last=Richardson|work=The Guardian|date=31 January 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref> He additionally came under fire from former Milan goalkeepers for his drops in performance; [[Fabio Cudicini]] opined in 2007 that Dida's mistakes were due to psychological factors,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/476093/milan-cudicini-dida-problema-psicologico|title=Milan: Cudicini 'Dida? Problema psicologico'|trans-title=Cudicini: 'Dida? His problem is psychological'|work=ESPN FC|language=Italian|date=26 October 2007|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> while [[Enrico Albertosi]] was more blunt, saying in 2009 that Dida was \"never a guarantee\" in the Milan goal, \"even when he was at his best\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2009/novembre/18/Albertosi_Dida_non_sicurezza__ga_10_091118041.shtml|title=Albertosi \"Dida non-d\u00e0 sicurezza\"|trans-title=Albertosi: \"Dida is not secure\"|work=archiviostorico.gazzetta.it|first=Alberto|last=Cerruti|language=Italian|date=18 November 2009|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Influence==\n{{quote box|\"In his own quiet way Dida has done a great deal to counter the prejudice that may linger on in the generation of [[Chico Anysio]].\"|source=\u2014Football journalist [[Tim Vickery]] in 2007.<ref name=\"vickery\"/> Anysio, a Brazilian actor and comedian, had disparaged black goalkeepers in a June 2006 article published in ''[[Lance!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.casaca.com.br/home/2006/06/11/opiniao-racista-de-chico-anysio-no-lance/|title=Opini\u00e3o racista de Chico Anysio no LANCE|trans-title=Chico Anysio's racist opinion in LANCE|work=casaca.com.br|language=Portuguese|date=11 June 2006|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916101602/http://www.casaca.com.br/home/2006/06/11/opiniao-racista-de-chico-anysio-no-lance/|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The article was reprinted on 31 October 2007, the same day as a match between [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]] and [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]], who respectively started black keepers in [[Bruno Fernandes de Souza|Bruno]] and [[Felipe Ventura dos Santos|Felipe]].<ref name=\"vickery\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7078413.stm |title=BBC Sport: Tim Vickery column|first=Tim|last=Vickery|work=BBC Sport|date=6 November 2007|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>|width=30%|}}\nDida is the first notable Afro-Brazilian goalkeeper to play for club and country since [[Moacir Barbosa Nascimento|Moacyr Barbosa]], who had starred for [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]] and earned seventeen caps for Brazil, but bore the blame for Uruguay's winning goal in the [[Uruguay v Brazil (1950 FIFA World Cup)|1950 World Cup final]], which resulted thereafter in discrimination against black goalkeepers in Brazilian football.<ref name=\"goleirosnegros\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/rio-2016-olympics/news/football/Rio-2016-Brazils-goalkeeper-Barbara-helps-bury-Barbosas-ghost/articleshow/53693221.cms|title=Rio 2016: Brazil's goalkeeper Barbara helps bury Barbosa's ghost|first=Siddharth|last=Saxenal|work=[[Times of India]]|date=14 August 2016|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref> Dida was hailed by Brazilian media outlets for breaking this barrier after making his 1995 national team debut,<ref name=\"desafia\"/> starting in the 1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica,<ref name=\"futebol\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2012/uncovering-brazil-there-were-11-of-us/|title=Uncovering Brazil: 'There Were 11 of Us'|first=Amlan|last=Chowdhury|work=thehardtackle.com|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> and particularly in 2006, when he became the first black keeper in 56 years to start in a World Cup for Brazil.<ref name=\"keeper\"/> On 27 May 2006, during a press conference in [[Weggis, Switzerland]], where the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o'' were holding public training sessions, Dida called for his countrymen to forgive Barbosa,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/ch/life_in/feature/Dida-asks-Brazil-to-forgive-Barbosa.html|title=Dida asks Brazil to forgive Barbosa|first=Diane|last=Renee|work=Expatica.com|date=12 May 2006|accessdate=13 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430091534/http://www.expatica.com/ch/life_in/feature/Dida-asks-Brazil-to-forgive-Barbosa.html|archivedate=30 April 2008}}</ref> and to instead remember his positive contributions to Brazilian football.<ref name=\"negro\">{{cite web|url=http://esporte.uol.com.br/copa/2006/ultnot/brasil/2006/05/27/ult3505u208.jhtm|title=Primeiro negro ap\u00f3s 50, Dida reclama reconhecimento a Barbosa|trans-title=Dida, first black after 50 years, requests recognition for Barbosa|work=esporte.uol.com.br|language=Portuguese|first1=Daniel|last1=Tozzi|first2=Jo\u00e3o Henrique|last2=Medice|date=27 May 2006|accessdate=13 August 2016}}</ref> On 11 June, two days before the ''Sele\u00e7\u00e3o's'' opening match against Croatia, ''[[Folha de S.Paulo]]'' commented, \"Black, [[Northeast Region, Brazil|Northeastern]], and in his thirties, Dida will break barriers for a Brazilian goalkeeper.\"<ref name=\"folha\"/> Though such accolades continued for Dida after the tournament and his international retirement,<ref name=\"vickery\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/ESP/Noticia/Arquivo/0,,AA1291817-4840,00-DIDA+O+HOMEM+QUE+QUEBROU+O+TABU.html|title=Dida, o homem que quebrou o tabu|first=Rodrigo|last=Sirico|work=GloboEsporte.com|language=Portuguese|date=1 October 2006|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref> he and Barbosa currently remain the only Afro-Brazilian keepers to have started a World Cup final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/10/julio-cesar-selection-brazil-no1-extend-unfortunate-record|title=J\u00falio C\u00e9sar\u2019s selection as Brazil\u2019s No1 is an uncomfortable statistic|first=Fernando|last=Duarte|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 June 2014|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/104-Race/8828-domestic-disputes|title=Domestic disputes|first=Robert|last=Shaw|work=[[When Saturday Comes]]|publisher=When Saturday Comes Ltd.|date=June 2011|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bolacomgravata.com.br/racismo-e-discriminacao-racial-um-tabu-no-futebol-brasileiro/|title=Racismo e discrimina\u00e7\u00e3o racial: um tabu no futebol brasileiro|trans-title=Racism and discrimination are taboos in Brazilian football|first=Elias|last=Aredes|work=bolacomgravata.com.br|language=Portuguese|date=5 May 2013|accessdate=16 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006014144/http://bolacomgravata.com.br/racismo-e-discriminacao-racial-um-tabu-no-futebol-brasileiro/|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn the club level, Dida's success with Milan is cited as a factor in the increased presence of black goalkeepers on Brazilian teams,<ref name=\"goleirosnegros\"/> and, along with Taffarel, influential in the increase in Brazilian keepers playing in Europe.<ref name=\"renan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/584/brazil/2009/03/25/1175299/exclusive-renan-on-valencia-economic-crisis-olympics-2010|title=Exclusive: Renan on Valencia, Economic Crisis, Olympics & 2010 World Cup|first=Andre|last=Baibich|work=Goal.com|date=25 March 2009|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[Zero Hora]]'' wrote that Dida had become the first black keeper since 1971 to play for Internacional upon his signing with the club in January 2014.<ref name=\"43anos\"/> Some goalkeepers have adopted his playing name as an homage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futbolecuador.com/site/equipo/aucas/ref.outcontrol/monterrey-adelanta-emotiva-entrevista-a-alexander-dida-dominguez-sobre-sus-origenes/68755|title=\"No ten\u00eda sueldo, era un vi\u00e1tico y le regal\u00e9 un TV a mi madre\": Monterrey adelanta emotiva entrevista a Alexander 'Dida' Dom\u00ednguez|first=David|last=Espinoza|work=futbolecuador.com|language=Spanish|date=14 July 2016|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/sc/futebol/times/metropolitano-sc/noticia/2014/07/goleiro-dida-do-metropolitano-realiza-sonho-e-enfrentara-o-idolo-homonimo.html|title=Goleiro Dida, do Metropolitano, realiza sonho e enfrentar\u00e1 o \u00eddolo hom\u00f4nimo|trans-title=Goalkeeper Dida, of (Clube Atl\u00e9tico) Metropolitano, realizes dream by facing his idol and namesake|work=GloboEsporte|language=Portuguese|date=2 July 2014|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.goal.com/sw/galeri/nyota-wa-ligi-kuu-wenye-aka-za-wachezaji-wa-majuu/2/ncl5o43uwn5r1f4na9iylinjp|title=Deogratius Munish 'Dida'\u2014Nyota wa ligi kuu wenye a.k.a. za wachezaji wa majuu|trans-title=The most popular Tanzanian Premier League star: About the major players|work=Goal.com|language=Swahili|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> or due to perceived physical resemblances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.com/portal/resultados/detalles/?idx=32608#.V4Z0wOlOTzK|title='Dida', el portero de titanio |author=Edwin Ramiro Giraldo Ruiz|work=ElMundo.com|language=Spanish|date=29 September 2006|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2015/m=11/news=olaroiu-al-ahli-used-to-playing-under-pressure-2733977.html|title=Olaroiu: Al Ahli used to playing under pressure|work=FIFA.com|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2017/11/01/59f9bb4aca4741bc778b4606.html|title=Moha stays in the first team because of Luca Zidane's absence|first=Hugo|last=Cerezo|work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=1 November 2017|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Nicknames==\nDida earned many nicknames in his club career, first at Cruzeiro with ''A muralha azul'' (\"Blue Wall\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guerreirodosgramados.com.br/dida-a-muralha-azul-629|title=Dida, a muralha azul|work=guerreirodosgramados.com.br|date=17 April 2009|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref> followed by ''S\u00e3o Dida'' (\"Saint Dida\")<ref name=\"placar899\"/> and ''O rei dos p\u00eanaltis'' (\"King of Penalties\") at Corinthians. [[Milan Channel]] announcer Carlo Pellegatti nicknamed him ''Baghera la pantera'' (a reference to [[Bagheera]] from ''[[The Jungle Book]]'') for his acrobatic saves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomilan.net/i_soprannomi_di_carlo_pellegatti.htm|title=I soprannomi di Carlo Pellegatti|trans-title=Carlo Pellegatti's nicknames|work=tuttomilan.net|language=Italian|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref> Dida was called ''L\u2019Ammiraglio'' (\"The Admiral\") by Milan supporters as a play on his first name in reference to [[Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson|Horatio Nelson]],<ref name=\"acmilan.com\"/> but conversely labeled ''Didastro'' (a [[portmanteau]] of his playing name and ''disastro'', Italian for \"disaster\") after poor performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2009/10/25/1583910/da-didastro-a-eroe-di-verona-sentite-di-carlo-dida-a-verona|title=Da DIDASTRO a eroe di Verona... sentite Di Carlo: \"Dida a Verona si esalta sempre\"|work=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=25 October 2009|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref> In February 2013, ''[[Placar]]'' ran a feature on Dida titled ''O Homem de Gelo'' (\"The Iceman\"), named such for his stolid personality during games.<ref name=\"placar0213\">Santos, Beto. ''O homem de gelo'' (\"The iceman\"). ''Revista Placar'' #1375 (February 2013), p. 43-48.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nDuring the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 Serie A season]], Dida was among multiple players, including [[Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n]], [[\u00c1lvaro Recoba]], and then-future Milan teammate [[Cafu]], who were implicated in a league scandal involving fraudulent European [[passport]]s.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Dida had joined Milan with a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] passport in order to gain [[European Union|EU]] status, as Milan had already met their limit on non-EU players at the time with Andriy Shevchenko, Serginho, and [[Croats|Croatian]] midfielder [[Zvonimir Boban]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11863/2185020/dida-will-make-milan-move|title=DIDA WILL MAKE MILAN MOVE|first=Patrick|last=Goss|work=Sky Sports|date=2000|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> However, following a routine check that revealed the document was illegal, Milan promptly re-registered him as a non-EU player.<ref name=\"passport\">{{cite web| url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11863_2194418,00.html | title = UEFA to probe Milan over Dida reports | publisher=Sky Sports | date = 29 October 2000}}</ref> In June 2001, the [[Italian Football Federation]] fined the club \u00a3314,000 and banned Dida from the league for one year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/europe/news/2001/0718/20010718passportbans.html|title=Bans upheld on appeal in Italian passport scandal|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=18 July 2001|accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> while [[FIFA]] imposed a yearlong ban from international play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11860/2212476/passport-scandal-recoba-banned-for-a-year|title=PASSPORT SCANDAL: RECOBA BANNED FOR A YEAR|first=Patrick|last=Goss|work=Sky Sports|date=June 2001 |accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> Milan loaned him back to Corinthians for the 2001\u201302 season in accordance with the league suspension. On 3 April 2003, following a court appearance in [[Milan]], Dida was handed a seven-month suspended prison sentence.<ref name=\"abcnews\">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2003-04-04/milan-keeper-dida-handed-suspended-sentence/1830012 | title = Milan keeper Dida handed suspended sentence | work=ABC News Australia | date = 4 April 2003 | accessdate =13 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nIn 1996, prior to the Summer Olympics, Dida and Brazil coach [[M\u00e1rio Zagallo]] filmed a [[Volkswagen Gol]] television commercial in which Zagallo implores ''\"sai do Gol\"'' (\"out of the Gol\", a pun on \"out of the goal\"), while Dida, who is seated inside the vehicle, has no dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fkVPlSy3rSM|title=1996 Volkswagen Gol commercial|language=Portuguese|work=YouTube|date=3 December 2006|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esporte.uol.com.br/futebol/ultimas-noticias/2012/10/19/lusa-celebra-dica-de-vampeta-com-dida-e-reivindica-badalacao-de-ceni-para-seu-goleiro.htm|title=Lusa celebra dica de Vampeta sobre Dida e reivindica badala\u00e7\u00e3o de Ceni para sue goleiro|first=Bruno|last=Freitas|work=esporte.uol.com.br|date=19 October 2012|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref> Italian jewelry manufacturer FIBO Steel featured Dida and Buffon in a 2005 advertising campaign for their \"FA1RPLAY\" metal jewelry collection,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibosteelusa.com/html/ourads.htm|title=Our Ads|work=fibosteelusa.com|date=2005|accessdate=12 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060111072141/http://www.fibosteelusa.com/html/ourads.htm|archivedate=11 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALnuaaTACLQ|title=Making of FIBO STEEL 'FA1RPLAY' Ad Campaign|work=Miami Metals (via YouTube)|date=12 August 2008|accessdate=12 August 2016}}</ref> and he modeled several items in their online catalog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibosteelusa.com/media/pdf/WebCat_sets_01.pdf |title=Necklace & Bracelet Sets (p. 10) |work=Miami Steel |date=2005 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207201518/http://www.fibosteelusa.com/media/pdf/WebCat_sets_01.pdf |archivedate=7 December 2006}}</ref> A longtime wearer of goalkeeping gloves from German sportswear manufacturer [[Reusch (company)|Reusch]], Dida appeared on the cover of their summer 2006 catalog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reuschuk.com/2.html|title=Our Heritage|work=reuschuk.com|accessdate=20 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006014057/http://reuschuk.com/2.html|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has otherwise featured in few endorsement opportunities in his career; he explained to ''Placar'' in 2001 that he was uninterested in [[Commercialization|commercializing]] his image.<ref name=\"placar1001\"/> He does not participate in [[social media]].<ref name=\"placar0213\"/>\n\nDida joined Milan teammates [[Paolo Maldini]], Andriy Shevchenko, [[Gennaro Gattuso]], [[Massimo Ambrosini]], and [[Alessandro Costacurta]] in filming a brief appearance in the 2006 Italian comedy ''[[Really SSSupercool: Chapter Two|Eccezzziunale veramente: Capitolo secondo...me]]'', in which the main character ([[Diego Abatantuono]]) selects the Milan side in a dream sequence and wants Dida to play in attack due to his being Brazilian, with Shevchenko in goal instead.<ref name=\"espngotta\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gossip.it/news/diego-abatantuono-una-festa-eccezzziunale-news.html|title=Diego Abatantuono, una festa eccezzziunale!|work=Gossip.it|author=Francesca Romana Domenici|language=Italian|date=8 November 2005|accessdate=11 August 2006}}</ref> In a scene from another Italian film released that year, ''[[The Caiman|Il caimano]]'', the title character (played by [[Silvio Orlando]]) is asked by his son whether Dida or Buffon is the better goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comunquemilan.it/album-di-famiglia/la-parata-quasi-invisibile/|title=La parata (quasi) invisibile|first=Giuseppe|last=Pastore|work=comunquemilan.it|language=Italian|date=29 March 2013|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Outside football==\nOn 18 December 2013, Dida gained Italian citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milannews.it/news/foto-mn-dida-ottiene-la-nazionalita-italiana-131492/|title=Dida ottiene la nazionalit\u00e0 italiana|first=Pietro|last=Mazzara|work=milannews.it|language=Italian|date=18 December 2013|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://calciomercato-milan.it/ex-milan-nelson-dida-diventa-cittadino-italiano-acquisita-la-doppia-nazionalita|title=EX MILAN, NELSON DIDA DIVENTA CITTADINO ITALIANO: ACQUISITA LA DOPPIA NAZIONALIT\u00c0|first=Alessandro|last=La Farina|work=calciomercato-milan.it|language=Italian|date=18 December 2013|accessdate=17 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006014023/http://calciomercato-milan.it/ex-milan-nelson-dida-diventa-cittadino-italiano-acquisita-la-doppia-nazionalita|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same year, a [[gym]]nasium in his home municipality of Lagoa da Canoa was named in his honor ''(Gin\u00e1sio de Esportes Nelson de Jesus Silva)'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minutoarapiraca.cadaminuto.com.br/noticia/11124/2013/07/11/alvaro-melo-avalia-primeiro-semestre-de-sua-gestao-e-anuncia-concurso-publico|title=\u00c1lvaro Melo avalia primeiro semestre de sua gest\u00e3o e anuncia concurs p\u00fablico|work=Minuto Arapiraca|language=Portuguese|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> and in April 2014, Dida met with its mayor \u00c1lvaro Melo to discuss the participation of children in athletics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minutoarapiraca.cadaminuto.com.br/noticia/14917/2014/12/28/alvaro-melo-e-goleiro-dida-discutem-importancia-do-esporte-em-lagoa-da-canoa|title=\u00c1lvaro Melo e goleiro Dida discutem import\u00e2ncia do esporte em Lagoa da Canoa|trans-title=Alvaro Melo and goalkeeper Dida discuss the importance of sports in Lagoa da Canoa|work=Minuto Arapiraca|language=Portuguese|date=28 April 2014|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> On 11 September 2015, Dida was named an honorary citizen of [[Alagoas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/al/noticia/2015/11/goleiro-do-inter-baiano-dida-recebe-titulo-de-cidadao-honorario-de-alagoas.html|title=Goleiro do Inter, baiano Dida recebe t\u00edtulo de cidad\u00e3o honor\u00e1rio de Alagoas|trans-title=Inter's Bahian keeper Dida receives title of honorary citizen of Alagoas|first=Denilson|last=Roma|work=Globo Esporte|language=Portuguese|date=11 September 2015|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Former [[left back]] [[Serginho (footballer, born 1971)|Serginho]], who played with Dida at Milan from 2000 to 2008, currently serves as his agent and manager.<ref name=\"surgiu\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Dida and then-Internacional teammates [[Juan Silveira dos Santos|Juan]] and [[Andr\u00e9s D'Alessandro]] filmed [[public service announcement]]s for the [[Pan American Health Organization]], which stressed the importance of [[vaccination]]s in order to prevent the spread of disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paho.org/bra/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4630:os-jogadores-de-futebol-do-brasil-e-da-argentina-participam-de-campanha-da-opasoms-que-incentiva-a-vacinacao-para-evitar-mais-de-20-doencas&Itemid=821|title=Os Jogadores de Futebol do Brasil e da Argentina participam de campanha da OPAS/OMS que incentiva a vacina\u00e7\u00e3o para evitar mais de 20 doen\u00e7as|trans-title=Brazilian and Argentinian footballers participate in PAHO/WHO campaign, encouraging vaccination to prevent more than 20 diseases|language=Portuguese|work=paho.org|date=28 April 2014|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2013 protests in Brazil|June 2013 protests in Brazil]] that occurred during the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|Confederations Cup]],<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/op-edge/brazil-world-cup-footballers-politics-601/|title=World Cup 2014: Why Brazilian footballers are fighting back, and getting political|first=Mauricio |last=Savarese|work=RT.com|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> Dida joined a host of Brazilian footballers including [[Rog\u00e9rio Ceni]], [[Gilberto Silva]], and former Milan teammates Clarence Seedorf and Alexandre Pato, in forming ''Bom Senso FC'' (Common Sense FC), an organization that sought to resolve the issues of timely player compensation and shortened offseasons in Brazilian club football.<ref name=\"RT\"/> On 19 March 2015, Dida delivered a speech at the [[Federal University of Paran\u00e1]] in [[Curitiba]] that discussed the organization's proposals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogdojuca.uol.com.br/2015/03/o-discurso-de-dida-em-nome-do-bom-senso-fc/|title=O discurso de Dida em nome do Bom Senso FC|trans-title=Dida's speech on behalf of Bom Senso FC|work=UOL Esporte|language=Portuguese|first=Juca|last=Kfouri|date=19 March 2015|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanas.ufpr.br/portal/historia/files/2016/04/Monografia-Rayanna-Farias-1.pdf|title=UM POUCO DE BOM SENSO: O PROCESSO DE REESTRUTURA\u00c7\u00c3O DO FUTEBOL BRASILEIRO|trans-title=A little Good Sense: the process of restructuring Brazilian football|first=Rayanda|last=Farias|work=humanas.ufpr.br|language=Portuguese|date=19 March 2015|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n\n{{updated| 14 November 2014}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"100\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"60\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Gls | Goals scored }}\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Gls | Goals scored }}\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Gls | Goals scored }}\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Gls | Goals scored }}\n!width=\"40\"|Apps\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Gls | Goals scored }}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria|Vit\u00f3ria]]'''\n||1992\n||-||-||-||-||-||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|1993\n||24||0||-||-||-||-||-||-||24||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|'''[[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]]'''\n||1994\n||23||0||-||-||6||7||-||-||29||0\n|-\n|1995\n||20||0||3||0||8||0||-||-||31||0\n|-\n|1996\n||22||0||9||0||?||?||-||-||31||0\n|-\n|1997\n||25||0||2||0||20||0||1||0||48||0\n|-\n|1998\n||30||0||5||0||14||0||-||-||49||0\n|-\n|'''[[FC Lugano|Lugano]]'''\n||1998\u201399\n||-||-||-||-||-||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]]'''\n||1999\n||25||0||-||-||-||-||-||-||25||0\n|-\n|2000\n||-||-||-||-||11||0||4||0||15||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|'''[[A.C. Milan|Milan]]'''\n||2000\u201301\n||1||0||-||-||6||0||-||-||7||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Sport Clu